# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rna-interference
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] The **Argonaute** protein family, first discovered for its evolutionarily conserved stem cell function, plays a central role in RNA silencing processes as essential components of the RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC).
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] RISC is responsible for the gene silencing phenomenon known as RNA interference (RNAi).
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Argonaute proteins bind different classes of small non-coding RNAs, including microRNAs (miRNAs), small interfering RNAs (siRNAs) and piwi-interacting RNAs (piRNAs).
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Small RNAs guide Argonaute proteins to their specific targets through sequence complementarity (base pairing), which then leads to mRNA cleavage, translation inhibition, and/or the initiation of mRNA decay.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] The name of this protein family is derived from a mutant phenotype resulting from mutation of AGO1 in *Arabidopsis thaliana*, which was likened by Bohmert et al. to the appearance of the pelagic octopus *Argonauta argo*.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] RNA interference (RNAi) is a biological process in which RNA molecules inhibit gene expression, via either destruction of specific mRNA molecules or suppressing translation.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] RNAi has a significant role in defending cells against parasitic nucleotide sequences .
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] In eukaryotes, including animals, RNAi is initiated by the enzyme Dicer.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Dicer cleaves long double-stranded RNA (dsRNA, often found in viruses and small interfering RNA) molecules into short double stranded fragments of around 20 nucleotide siRNAs.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] The dsRNA is then separated into two single-stranded RNAs (ssRNA) – the passenger strand and the guide strand.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Subsequently, the passenger strand is degraded, while the guide strand is incorporated into the RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC).
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] The most well-studied outcome of the RNAi is post-transcriptional gene silencing, which occurs when the guide strand pairs with a complementary sequence in a messenger RNA molecule and induces cleavage by Argonaute, that lies in the core of RNA-induced silencing complex.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Argonaute proteins are the active part of RNA-induced silencing complex, cleaving the target mRNA strand complementary to their bound siRNA.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Theoretically the dicer produces short double-stranded fragments so there should be also two functional single-stranded siRNA produced.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] But only one of the two single-stranded RNA here will be utilized to base pair with target mRNA.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] It is known as the guide strand, which is incorporated into the Argonaute protein and leads gene silencing.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] The other single-stranded RNA, named the passenger strand, is degraded during the RNA-induced silencing complex process.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Once the Argonaute is associated with the small RNA, the enzymatic activity conferred by the PIWI domain cleaves only the passenger strand of the small interfering RNA.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] RNA strand separation and incorporation into the Argonaute protein are guided by the strength of the hydrogen bond interaction at the 5′-ends of the RNA duplex, known as the asymmetry rule.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Also the degree of complementarity between the two strands of the intermediate RNA duplex defines how the miRNA are sorted into different types of Argonaute proteins.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] In animals, Argonaute associated with miRNA binds to the 3′-untranslated region of mRNA and prevents the production of proteins in various ways.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] The recruitment of Argonaute proteins to targeted mRNA can induce mRNA degradation.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] The Argonaute-miRNA complex can also affect the formation of functional ribosomes at the 5′-end of the mRNA.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] The complex here competes with the translation initiation factors and/or abrogate ribosome assembly.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Also, the Argonaute-miRNA complex can adjust protein production by recruiting cellular factors such as peptides or post translational modifying enzymes, which degrade the growing of polypeptides.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] The Argonaute (AGO) gene family encodes six characteristic domains: N- terminal (N), Linker-1 (L1), PAZ, Linker-2 (L2), Mid, and a C-terminal PIWI domain.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] The PAZ domain is named for *Drosophila* Piwi, *Arabidopsis* Argonaute-1, and *Arabidopsis* Zwille (also known as pinhead, and later renamed argonaute-10), where the domain was first recognized to be conserved.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] The PAZ domain is an RNA binding module that recognizes single-stranded 3′ ends of siRNA, miRNA and piRNA, in a sequence independent manner.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] PIWI is named after the Drosophila Piwi protein.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Structurally resembling RNaseH, the PIWI domain is essential for the target cleavage.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] The active site with aspartate–aspartate–glutamate triad harbors a divalent metal ion, necessary for the catalysis.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Family members of AGO that lost this conserved feature during evolution lack the cleavage activity.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] In human AGO, the PIWI motif also mediates protein-protein interaction at the PIWI box, where it binds to Dicer at an RNase III domain.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] At the interface of PIWI and Mid domains sits the 5′ phosphate of a siRNA, miRNA or piRNA, which is found essential in the functionality.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Within Mid lies a MC motif, a homologue structure proposed to mimic the cap-binding structure motif found in eIF4E.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] In humans, there are eight AGO family members, some of which are investigated intensively.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] However, even though AGO1–4 are capable of loading miRNA, endonuclease activity and thus RNAi-dependent gene silencing exclusively belongs to AGO2.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Considering the sequence conservation of PAZ and PIWI domains across the family, the uniqueness of AGO2 is presumed to arise from either the N-terminus or the spacing region linking PAZ and PIWI motifs.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Several AGO family members in plants also attract study.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] AGO1 is involved in miRNA related RNA degradation, and plays a central role in morphogenesis.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] In some organisms, it is strictly required for epigenetic silencing.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] AGO4 does not involve in RNAi directed RNA degradation, but in DNA methylation and other epigenetic regulation, through small RNA (smRNA) pathway.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] AGO7 has a function distinct from AGO 1 and 10, and is not found in gene silencing induced by transgenes.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Instead, it is related to developmental timing in plants.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Argonaute proteins were reported to be associated with cancers.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] It has been reported several tiny non-coding RNAs(microRNAs) are related with human cancers, like miR-15a and miR-16a are frequently deleted and/or down-regulated in patients.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] Even though the biological functions of miRNAs are not fully understood, the roles for miRNAs in the coordination of cell proliferation and cell death during development and metabolism have been uncovered.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] It is trusted that the miRNAs can direct negative or positive regulation at different levels, which depends on the specific miRNAs and target base pair interaction and the cofactors that recognize them.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] The small interfering RNAs produced by Dicer cause sequence specific, post-transcriptional gene silencing by guiding an endonuclease, the RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC), to mRNA.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] This process has been seen in a wide range of organisms, such as *Neurospora* fungus (in which it is known as quelling), plants (post-transcriptional gene silencing) and mammalian cells(RNAi).
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] If there is a complete or near complete sequence complementarity between the small RNA and the target, the Argonaute protein component of RISC mediates cleavage of the target transcript, the mechanism involves repression of translation predominantly.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] In 2016, a group from Hebei University of Science and Technology reported genome editing using a prokaryotic Argonaute protein from *Natronobacterium gregoryi*.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] However, evidence for application of Argonaute proteins as DNA-guided nucleases for genome editing have been questioned, with the retraction of the claim from the leading journal.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] In 2017, a group from University of Illinois reported using a prokaryotic Argonaute protein taken from *Pyrococcus furiosus* (PfAgo) along with guide DNA to edit DNA *in vitro* as artificial restriction enzymes.
[src:rna-interference/argonaute] PfAgo based artificial restriction enzymes were also used for storing data on native DNA sequences via enzymatic nicking.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Dicer was given its name in 2001 by Stony Brook PhD student Emily Bernstein while conducting research in Gregory Hannon's lab at Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Bernstein sought to discover the enzyme responsible for generating small RNA fragments from double-stranded RNA.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Dicer's ability to generate around 22 nucleotide RNA fragments was discovered by separating it from the RISC enzyme complex after initiating the RNAi pathway with dsRNA transfection.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] This experiment showed that RISC was not responsible for generating the observable small nucleotide fragments.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Subsequent experiments testing RNase III family enzymes abilities to create RNA fragments narrowed the search to *Drosophila* CG4792, now named Dicer.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Dicer orthologs are present in many other organisms.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] In the moss *Physcomitrella patens* DCL1b, one of four DICER proteins, is not involved in miRNA biogenesis but in dicing miRNA target transcripts.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Thus, a novel mechanism for regulation of gene expression, the epigenetic silencing of genes by miRNAs, was discovered.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] In terms of crystal structure, the first Dicer to be explored was that from the protozoan *Giardia intestinalis*.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] The work was done by Ian MacRae while conducting research as a postdoctoral fellow in Jennifer Doudna's lab at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] A PAZ domain and two RNase III domains were discovered by X-ray crystallography.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] The protein size is 82 kDa, representing the conserved functional core that has subsequently been found in larger Dicer proteins in other organisms; for example, it is 219 kDa in humans.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] The difference in size from humans to *G. intestinalis* Dicer is due to at least five different domains being present within human Dicer.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] These domains are important in Dicer activity regulation, dsRNA processing, and RNA interference protein factor functioning.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Human Dicer (also known as hsDicer or DICER1) is classified a Ribonuclease III because it cleaves double-stranded RNA.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] In addition to two RNaseIII domains, it contains a helicase domain, a PAZ (Piwi/Argonaute/Zwille) domain, and two double stranded RNA binding domains (DUF283 and dsRBD).
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Current research suggests the PAZ domain is capable of binding the 2 nucleotide 3' overhang of dsRNA while the RNaseIII catalytic domains form a pseudo-dimer around the dsRNA to initiate cleavage of the strands.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] This results in a functional shortening of the dsRNA strand.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] The distance between the PAZ and RNaseIII domains is determined by the angle of the connector helix and influences the length of the micro RNA product.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] The dsRBD domain binds the dsRNA, although the specific binding site of the domain has not been defined.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] It is possible that this domain works as part of a complex with other regulator proteins (TRBP in humans, R2D2, Loqs in *Drosophila*) in order to effectively position the RNaseIII domains and thus control the specificity of the sRNA products.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] The helicase domain has been implicated in processing long substrates.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] RNA interference is a process where the breakdown of RNA molecules into a microRNA (miRNA) inhibits gene expression of specific host mRNA sequences. miRNA is produced within the cell starting from primary miRNA (pri-miRNA) in the nucleus.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] These long sequences are cleaved into smaller precursor miRNA (pre-miRNA), which are usually 70 nucleotides with a hairpin structure.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Pri-miRNA are identified by DGCR8 and cleaved by Drosha to form the pre-miRNA, a process that occurs in the nucleus.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] These pre-miRNA are then exported to the cytoplasm, where they are cleaved by Dicer to form mature miRNA.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Small interfering RNA (siRNA) are produced and function in a similar manner to miRNA by cleaving double-stranded RNA with Dicer into smaller fragments, 21 to 23 nucleotides in length.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Both miRNAs and siRNAs activate the RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC), which finds the complementary target mRNA sequence and cleaves the RNA using RNase.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] In general, RNA interference is an essential part of normal processes within organisms such as humans, and it is an area being researched as a diagnostic and therapeutic tool for cancer targets.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Age related macular degeneration is a prominent cause of blindness in developed countries.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Dicer's role in this disease became apparent after it was discovered that affected patients showed decreased levels of Dicer in their retinal pigment epithelium (RPE).
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Mice with Dicer knocked out, lacking Dicer only in their RPE, exhibited similar symptoms.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] However, other mice lacking important RNAi pathway proteins like Drosha and Pasha, did not have symptoms of macular degeneration as Dicer-knockout mice.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] This observation suggested a Dicer specific role in retinal health that was independent of the RNAi pathway and thus not a function of si/miRNA generation.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] A form of RNA called Alu RNA (the RNA transcripts of alu elements)) was found to be elevated in patients with insufficient Dicer levels.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] These non coding strands of RNA can loop forming dsRNA structures that would be degraded by Dicer in a healthy retina.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] However, with insufficient Dicer levels, the accumulation of alu RNA leads to the degeneration of RPE as a result of inflammation.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Altered miRNA expression profiles in malignant cancers suggest a pivotal role of miRNA and thus dicer in cancer development and prognosis. miRNAs can function as tumor suppressors and therefore their altered expression may result in tumorigenesis.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] In analysis of lung and ovarian cancer, poor prognosis and decreased patient survival times correlate with decreased dicer and drosha expression.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Decreased Dicer mRNA levels correlate with advanced tumor stage.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] However, high dicer expression in other cancers, like prostate and esophageal, has been shown to correlate with poor patient prognosis.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] This discrepancy between cancer types suggests unique RNAi regulatory processes involving dicer differ amongst different tumor types.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] DNA damage increases in mammalian cells with decreased Dicer expression as a result of decreased efficiency of DNA damage repair and other mechanisms.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] For example, siRNA from double strand breaks (produced by Dicer) may act as guides for protein complexes involved in the double strand break repair mechanisms and can also direct chromatin modifications.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Additionally, miRNAs expression patterns change as a result of DNA damage caused by ionizing or ultraviolet radiation.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] RNAi mechanisms are responsible for transposon silencing and in their absence, as when Dicer is knocked out/down, can lead to activated transposons that cause DNA damage.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Accumulation of DNA damage may result in cells with oncogenic mutations and thus the development of a tumor.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Multinodular goiter with schwannomatosis has been shown to be an autosomal dominant condition associated with mutations in this gene.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Infection by RNA viruses can trigger the RNAi cascade.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] It is likely Dicer is involved in viral immunity as viruses that infect both plant and animal cells contain proteins designed to inhibit the RNAi response.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] In humans, the viruses HIV-1, influenza, and vaccinia encode such RNAi suppressing proteins.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Inhibition of dicer is beneficial to the virus as dicer is able to cleave viral dsRNA and load the product onto RISC resulting in targeted degradation of viral mRNA; thus fighting the infection.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Another potential mechanism for viral pathogenesis is the blockade of dicer as a way to inhibit cellular miRNA pathways.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Dicer can be used to identify whether tumors are present within the body based on the expression level of the enzyme.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] A study showed that many patients that had cancer had decreased expression levels of Dicer.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] The same study showed that lower Dicer expression correlated with lower patient survival length.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Along with being a diagnostic tool, Dicer can be used for treating patients by injecting foreign siRNA intravenously to cause gene silencing.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] The siRNA was shown to be delivered in two ways in mammalian species such as mice.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] One way would be to directly inject into the system, which would not require Dicer function.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Another way would be to introduce it by plasmids that encode for short hairpin RNA, which are cleaved by Dicer into siRNA.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] One of the advantages of using Dicer to produce siRNA therapeutically would be the specificity and diversity of targets it can affect compared to what is currently being used such as antibodies or small molecular inhibitors.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] In general, small molecular inhibitors are difficult in terms of specificity along with unendurable side effects.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Antibodies are as specific as siRNA, but it is limited by only being able to be used against ligands or surface receptors.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] On the other hand, low efficiency of intracellular uptake is the main obstacle of injection of siRNA.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Injected SiRNA has poor stability in blood and causes stimulations of non-specific immunity.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Also, producing miRNA therapeutically lacks in specificity because only 6-8 nucleotide base pairing is required for miRNA to attach to mRNA.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] In *Drosophila*, Dicer-1 generates microRNAs (miRNAs) by processing pre-miRNA, Dicer-2 is responsible for producing small interfering RNAs (siRNAs) from long double-stranded RNA (dsRNA).
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Insects can use Dicer as a potent antiviral.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] This finding is especially significant given that mosquitoes are responsible for the transmission of many viral diseases including the potentially deadly arboviruses: West Nile virus, dengue fever and yellow fever.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] While mosquitoes, more specifically the *Aedes aegypti* species, serve as the vectors for these viruses, they are not the intended host of the virus.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Transmission occurs as a result of the female mosquito's need for vertebrate blood to develop her eggs.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] The RNAi pathway in insects is very similar to that of other animals; Dicer-2 cleaves viral RNA and loads it onto the RISC complex where one strand serves as a template for the production of RNAi products and the other is degraded.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Insects with mutations leading to non-functional components of their RNAi pathway show increased viral loads for viruses they carry or increased susceptibility to viruses for which they are hosts.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Similarly to humans, insect viruses have evolved mechanisms to avoid the RNAi pathway.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] As an example, *Drosophila C* virus encodes for protein 1A which binds to dsRNA thus protecting it from dicer cleavage as well as RISC loading.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] *Heliothis virescens* ascovirus 3a encodes an RNase III enzyme similar to the RNase III domains of dicer which may compete for dsRNA substrate as well as degrade siRNA duplexes to prevent RISC loading.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Plant genomes encode Dicer-like proteins with similar functions and protein domains as animal and insect Dicers.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] For example, in the model organism *Arabidopsis thaliana*, four Dicer-like-encoding genes have been described and are designated DCL1 to DCL4; there are four Dicer family proteins encoded in a typical eudicot genome.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] DCL1 is involved with miRNA generation and sRNA production from inverted repeats.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] DCL2 creates siRNA from cis-acting antisense transcripts which aid in viral immunity and defense.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] DCL3 generates heterochromatic siRNAs which direct and reinforce DNA methylation and chromatin modifications; DCL4 is involved in trans-acting siRNA metabolism and transcript silencing at the post-transcriptional level.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] The genomes of most monocots including rice and maize encode a fifth DCL protein, Dicer-like 5 or DCL5.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] Originally called DCL3b due to its emergence from a monocot-specific duplication of DCL3, DCL5 plays an important role in male reproductive development.
[src:rna-interference/dicer] The name of DCL5 was originally proposed based on its divergence within rice and conservation in other grasses, which led to the speculation that it had a distinct function.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In cells of humans and other animals, miRNAs primarily act by destabilizing the mRNA.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] miRNAs resemble the small interfering RNAs (siRNAs) of the RNA interference (RNAi) pathway, except miRNAs derive from regions of RNA transcripts that fold back on themselves to form short stem-loops (hairpins), whereas siRNAs derive from longer regions of double-stranded RNA.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The human genome may encode over 1900 miRNAs, However, only about 500 human miRNAs represent *bona fide* miRNAs in the manually curated miRNA gene database MirGeneDB.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] miRNAs are abundant in many mammalian cell types.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] They appear to target about 60% of the genes of humans and other mammals.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Many miRNAs are evolutionarily conserved, which implies that they have important biological functions.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] For example, 90 families of miRNAs have been conserved since at least the common ancestor of mammals and fish, and most of these conserved miRNAs have important functions, as shown by studies in which genes for one or more members of a family have been knocked out in mice.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In 2024, American scientists Victor Ambros and Gary Ruvkun were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their work on the discovery of miRNA and its role in post-transcriptional gene regulation.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The first miRNA was discovered in the early 1990s.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] However, they were not recognized as a distinct class of biological regulators until the early 2000s.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Research revealed different sets of miRNAs expressed in different cell types and tissues and multiple roles for miRNAs in plant and animal development and in many other biological processes.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Aberrant miRNA expression are implicated in disease states.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] MiRNA-based therapies are under investigation.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The first miRNA was discovered in 1993 by a group led by Victor Ambros and including Lee and Feinbaum.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] However, additional insight into its mode of action required simultaneously published work by Gary Ruvkun's team, including Wightman and Ha.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] These groups published back-to-back papers on the *lin-4* gene, which was known to control the timing of *C. elegans* larval development by repressing the *lin-14* gene.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] When Lee et al. isolated the *lin-4* miRNA, they found that instead of producing an mRNA encoding a protein, it produced short non-coding RNAs, one of which was a ~22-nucleotide RNA that contained sequences partially complementary to multiple sequences in the 3' UTR of the *lin-14* mRNA.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] This complementarity was proposed to inhibit the translation of the *lin-14* mRNA into the LIN-14 protein.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] At the time, the *lin-4* small RNA was thought to be a nematode idiosyncrasy.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In 2000, a second small RNA was characterized: *let-7* RNA, which represses *lin-41* to promote a later developmental transition in *C. elegans*.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The *let-7* RNA was found to be conserved in many species, leading to the suggestion that *let-7* RNA and additional "small temporal RNAs" might regulate the timing of development in diverse animals, including humans.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] A year later, the *lin-4* and *let-7* RNAs were found to be part of a large class of small RNAs present in *C. elegans*, *Drosophila* and human cells.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The many RNAs of this class resembled the *lin-4* and *let-7* RNAs, except their expression patterns were usually inconsistent with a role in regulating the timing of development.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] This suggested that most might function in other types of regulatory pathways.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] At this point, researchers started using the term "microRNA" to refer to this class of small regulatory RNAs.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The first human disease associated with deregulation of miRNAs was chronic lymphocytic leukemia.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In this disorder, the miRNAs have a dual role working as both tumor suppressors and oncogenes.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Under a standard nomenclature system, names are assigned to experimentally confirmed miRNAs before publication.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] For animal miRNAs, the prefix "miR" is followed by a dash and a number, the latter often indicating order of naming.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] For example, miR-124 was named and likely discovered prior to miR-456.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] A capitalized "miR-" refers to the mature form of the miRNA, while the uncapitalized "mir-" refers to the pre-miRNA and the pri-miRNA.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The convention for naming plant miRNAs excludes the hyphen; for example, miR156 or miR172 are well-described plant miRNAs.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The genes encoding miRNAs are also named using the same three-letter prefix according to the conventions of the organism gene nomenclature.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] For examples, the official miRNAs gene names in some organisms are *mir-1* in *C. elegans* and *Drosophila,* *Mir1* in *Rattus norvegicus,* *MIR25* in human, and *MIR156* and *MIR172* in Arabidopsis.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] miRNAs with nearly identical sequences except for one or two nucleotides are annotated with an additional lower case letter.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] For example, miR-124a is closely related to miR-124b.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Pre-miRNAs, pri-miRNAs and genes that lead to 100% identical mature miRNAs but that are located at different places in the genome are indicated with an additional dash-number suffix.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] For example, the pre-miRNAs hsa-mir-194-1 and hsa-mir-194-2 lead to an identical mature miRNA (hsa-miR-194) but are from genes located in different genome regions.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Species of origin is designated with a three-letter prefix, e.g., hsa-miR-124 is a human (*Homo sapiens*) miRNA and oar-miR-124 is a sheep (*Ovis aries*) miRNA.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Other common prefixes include "v" for viral (miRNA encoded by a viral genome) and "d" for *Drosophila* miRNA (a fruit fly commonly studied in genetic research).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] When two mature microRNAs originate from opposite arms of the same pre-miRNA and are found in roughly similar amounts, they are denoted with a -3p or -5p suffix.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] (In the past, this distinction was also made with "s" (sense) and "as" (antisense)).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] However, the mature microRNA found from one arm of the hairpin is usually much more abundant than that found from the other arm, in which case, an asterisk following the name indicates the mature species found at low levels from the opposite arm of a hairpin.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] For example, miR-124 and miR-124* share a pre-miRNA hairpin, but much more miR-124 is found in the cell.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Plant miRNAs usually have near-perfect pairing with their mRNA targets, which induces gene repression through cleavage of the target transcripts.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In contrast, animal miRNAs are able to recognize their target mRNAs by using as few as 6–8 nucleotides (the seed region) at the 5' end of the miRNA, which is not enough pairing to induce cleavage of the target mRNAs.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Combinatorial regulation is a feature of miRNA regulation in animals.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] A given miRNA may have hundreds of different mRNA targets, and a given target might be regulated by multiple miRNAs.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Estimates of the average number of unique messenger RNAs that are targets for repression by a typical miRNA vary, depending on the estimation method, but multiple approaches show that mammalian miRNAs can have many unique targets.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] For example, an analysis of the miRNAs highly conserved in vertebrates shows that each has, on average, roughly 400 conserved targets.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Likewise, experiments show that a single miRNA species can reduce the stability of hundreds of unique messenger RNAs.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Other experiments show that a single miRNA species may repress the production of hundreds of proteins, but that this repression often is relatively mild (much less than 2-fold).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] As many as 40% of miRNA genes may lie in the introns or even exons of other genes.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] These are usually, though not exclusively, found in a sense orientation, and thus usually are regulated together with their host genes.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The DNA template is not the final word on mature miRNA production: 6% of human miRNAs show RNA editing (isomiRs), the site-specific modification of RNA sequences to yield products different from those encoded by their DNA.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] This increases the diversity and scope of miRNA action beyond that implicated from the genome alone.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] miRNA genes are usually transcribed by RNA polymerase II (Pol II).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The polymerase often binds to a promoter found near the DNA sequence, encoding what will become the hairpin loop of the pre-miRNA.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The resulting transcript is capped with a specially modified nucleotide at the 5' end, polyadenylated with multiple adenosines (a poly(A) tail), and spliced.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Animal miRNAs are initially transcribed as part of one arm of an ~80 nucleotide RNA hairpin that in turn forms part of a several hundred nucleotide-long miRNA precursor termed a pri-miRNA.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] When a hairpin precursor is found in the 3' UTR, a transcript may serve as a pri-miRNA and a mRNA.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] RNA polymerase III (Pol III) transcribes some miRNAs, especially those with upstream Alu sequences, transfer RNAs (tRNAs), and mammalian wide interspersed repeat (MWIR) promoter units.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] A single pri-miRNA may contain from one to six miRNA precursors.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] These hairpin loop structures are composed of about 70 nucleotides each.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Each hairpin is flanked by sequences necessary for efficient processing.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The double-stranded RNA (dsRNA) structure of the hairpins in a pri-miRNA is recognized by a nuclear protein known as DiGeorge Syndrome Critical Region 8 (DGCR8 or "Pasha" in invertebrates), named for its association with DiGeorge Syndrome.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] DGCR8 associates with the enzyme Drosha, a protein that cuts RNA, to form the microprocessor complex.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In this complex, DGCR8 orients the catalytic RNase III domain of Drosha to liberate hairpins from pri-miRNAs by cleaving RNA about eleven nucleotides from the hairpin base (one helical dsRNA turn into the stem).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The product resulting has a two-nucleotide overhang at its 3' end; it has 3' hydroxyl and 5' phosphate groups.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] It is often termed as a pre-miRNA (precursor-miRNA).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Sequence motifs downstream of the pre-miRNA that are important for efficient processing have been identified.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Pre-miRNAs that are spliced directly out of introns, bypassing the microprocessor complex, are known as "mirtrons." Mirtrons have been found in *Drosophila*, *C. elegans*, and mammals.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] As many as 16% of pre-miRNAs may be altered through nuclear RNA editing.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Most commonly, enzymes known as adenosine deaminases acting on RNA (ADARs) catalyze adenosine to inosine (A to I) transitions.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] RNA editing can halt nuclear processing (for example, of pri-miR-142, leading to degradation by the ribonuclease Tudor-SN) and alter downstream processes including cytoplasmic miRNA processing and target specificity (e.g., by changing the seed region of miR-376 in the central nervous system).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Pre-miRNA hairpins are exported from the nucleus in a process involving the nucleocytoplasmic shuttler Exportin-5.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] This protein, a member of the karyopherin family, recognizes a two-nucleotide overhang left by the RNase III enzyme Drosha at the 3' end of the pre-miRNA hairpin.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Exportin-5-mediated transport to the cytoplasm is energy-dependent, using guanosine triphosphate (GTP) bound to the Ran protein.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In the cytoplasm, the pre-miRNA hairpin is cleaved by the RNase III enzyme Dicer.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] This endoribonuclease interacts with 5' and 3' ends of the hairpin and cuts away the loop joining the 3' and 5' arms, yielding an imperfect miRNA:miRNA* duplex about 22 nucleotides in length.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Overall hairpin length and loop size influence the efficiency of Dicer processing.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The imperfect nature of the miRNA:miRNA* pairing also affects cleavage.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Some of the G-rich pre-miRNAs can potentially adopt the G-quadruplex structure as an alternative to the canonical hairpin structure.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] For example, human pre-miRNA 92b adopts a G-quadruplex structure which is resistant to the Dicer mediated cleavage in the cytoplasm.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Although either strand of the duplex may potentially act as a functional miRNA, only one strand is usually incorporated into the RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC) where the miRNA and its mRNA target interact.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] While the majority of miRNAs are located within the cell, some miRNAs, commonly known as circulating miRNAs or extracellular miRNAs, have also been found in extracellular environment, including various biological fluids and cell culture media.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] miRNA biogenesis in plants differs from animal biogenesis mainly in the steps of nuclear processing and export.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Instead of being cleaved by two different enzymes, once inside and once outside the nucleus, both cleavages of the plant miRNA are performed by a Dicer homolog, called Dicer-like1 (DL1).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] DL1 is expressed only in the nucleus of plant cells, which indicates that both reactions take place inside the nucleus.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Before plant miRNA:miRNA* duplexes are transported out of the nucleus, its 3' overhangs are methylated by a RNA methyltransferaseprotein called Hua-Enhancer1 (HEN1).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The duplex is then transported out of the nucleus to the cytoplasm by a protein called Hasty (HST), an Exportin 5 homolog, where they disassemble and the mature miRNA is incorporated into the RISC.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The mature miRNA is part of an active RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC) containing Dicer and many associated proteins.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Dicer processing of the pre-miRNA is thought to be coupled with unwinding of the duplex.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Generally, only one strand is incorporated into the miRISC, selected on the basis of its thermodynamic instability and weaker base-pairing on the 5' end relative to the other strand.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The position of the hairpin may also influence strand choice.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The other strand, called the passenger strand due to its lower levels in the steady state, is denoted with an asterisk (*) and is normally degraded.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In some cases, both strands of the duplex are viable and become functional miRNA that target different mRNA populations.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Members of the Argonaute (Ago) protein family are central to RISC function.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Argonautes are needed for miRNA-induced silencing and contain two conserved RNA binding domains: a PAZ domain that can bind the single stranded 3' end of the mature miRNA and a PIWI domain that structurally resembles ribonuclease-H and functions to interact with the 5' end of the guide strand.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] They bind the mature miRNA and orient it for interaction with a target mRNA.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Some argonautes, for example human Ago2, cleave target transcripts directly; argonautes may also recruit additional proteins to achieve translational repression.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The human genome encodes eight argonaute proteins divided by sequence similarities into two families: AGO (with four members present in all mammalian cells and called E1F2C/hAgo in humans), and PIWI (found in the germline and hematopoietic stem cells).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Gene silencing may occur either via mRNA degradation or preventing mRNA from being translated.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] For example, miR16 contains a sequence complementary to the AU-rich element found in the 3'UTR of many unstable mRNAs, such as TNF alpha or GM-CSF.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] It has been demonstrated that given complete complementarity between the miRNA and target mRNA sequence, Ago2 can cleave the mRNA and lead to direct mRNA degradation.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In the absence of complementarity, silencing is achieved by preventing translation.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The relation of miRNA and its target mRNA can be based on the simple negative regulation of a target mRNA, but it seems that a common scenario is the use of a "coherent feed-forward loop", "mutual negative feedback loop" (also termed double negative loop) and "positive feedback/feed-forward loop".
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Some miRNAs work as buffers of random gene expression changes arising due to stochastic events in transcription, translation and protein stability.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Such regulation is typically achieved by the virtue of negative feedback loops or incoherent feed-forward loop uncoupling protein output from mRNA transcription.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Turnover of mature miRNA is needed for rapid changes in miRNA expression profiles.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] During miRNA maturation in the cytoplasm, uptake by the Argonaute protein is thought to stabilize the guide strand, while the opposite (* or "passenger") strand is preferentially destroyed.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In what has been called a "Use it or lose it" strategy, Argonaute may preferentially retain miRNAs with many targets over miRNAs with few or no targets, leading to degradation of the non-targeting molecules.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Decay of mature miRNAs in *Caenorhabditis elegans* is mediated by the 5'-to-3' exoribonuclease XRN2, also known as Rat1p.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In plants, SDN (small RNA degrading nuclease) family members degrade miRNAs in the opposite (3'-to-5') direction.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Similar enzymes are encoded in animal genomes, but their roles have not been described.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Several miRNA modifications affect miRNA stability.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] As indicated by work in the model organism *Arabidopsis thaliana* (thale cress), mature plant miRNAs appear to be stabilized by the addition of methyl moieties at the 3' end.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The 2'-O-conjugated methyl groups block the addition of uracil (U) residues by uridyltransferase enzymes, a modification that may be associated with miRNA degradation.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] However, uridylation may also protect some miRNAs; the consequences of this modification are incompletely understood.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Uridylation of some animal miRNAs has been reported.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Both plant and animal miRNAs may be altered by addition of adenine (A) residues to the 3' end of the miRNA.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] An extra A added to the end of mammalian miR-122, a liver-enriched miRNA important in hepatitis C, stabilizes the molecule and plant miRNAs ending with an adenine residue have slower decay rates.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The function of miRNAs appears to be in gene regulation.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] For that purpose, a miRNA is complementary to a part of one or more messenger RNAs (mRNAs).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Animal miRNAs are usually complementary to a site in the 3' UTR whereas plant miRNAs are usually complementary to coding regions of mRNAs.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Perfect or near perfect base pairing with the target RNA promotes cleavage of the RNA.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] This is the primary mode of plant miRNAs.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] For partially complementary microRNAs to recognise their targets, nucleotides 2–7 of the miRNA (its 'seed region') must be perfectly complementary.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Animal miRNAs inhibit protein translation of the target mRNA (this is present but less common in plants).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Partially complementary microRNAs can also speed up deadenylation, causing mRNAs to be degraded sooner.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] While degradation of miRNA-targeted mRNA is well documented, whether or not translational repression is accomplished through mRNA degradation, translational inhibition, or a combination of the two is hotly debated.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Recent work on miR-430 in zebrafish, as well as on bantam-miRNA and miR-9 in *Drosophila* cultured cells, shows that translational repression is caused by the disruption of translation initiation, independent of mRNA deadenylation.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] miRNAs occasionally also cause histone modification and DNA methylation of promoter sites, which affects the expression of target genes.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] It is often impossible to discern these mechanisms using experimental data about stationary reaction rates.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Nevertheless, they are differentiated in dynamics and have different *kinetic signatures*.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Unlike plant microRNAs, the animal microRNAs target diverse genes.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] However, genes involved in functions common to all cells, such as gene expression, have relatively fewer microRNA target sites and seem to be under selection to avoid targeting by microRNAs.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] There is a strong correlation between *ITPR* gene regulations and mir-92 and mir-19.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] dsRNA can also activate gene expression, a mechanism that has been termed "small RNA-induced gene activation" or RNAa. dsRNAs targeting gene promoters can induce potent transcriptional activation of associated genes.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] This was demonstrated in human cells using synthetic dsRNAs termed small activating RNAs (saRNAs), but has also been demonstrated for endogenous microRNA.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Given the name "competing endogenous RNAs" (ceRNAs), these microRNAs bind to "microRNA response elements" on genes and pseudogenes and may provide another explanation for the persistence of non-coding DNA.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] miRNAs are also found as extracellular **circulating miRNAs**.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Circulating miRNAs are released into body fluids including blood and cerebrospinal fluid and have the potential to be available as biomarkers in a number of diseases.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Some researches show that mRNA cargo of exosomes may have a role in implantation, they can savage an adhesion between trophoblast and endometrium or support the adhesion by down regulating or up regulating expression of genes involved in adhesion/invasion.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Moreover, miRNA as miR-183/96/182 seems to play a key role in circadian rhythm.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] miRNAs are well conserved in both plants and animals, and are thought to be a vital and evolutionarily ancient component of gene regulation.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] While core components of the microRNA pathway are conserved between plants and animals, miRNA repertoires in the two kingdoms appear to have emerged independently with different primary modes of action.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] microRNAs are useful phylogenetic markers because of their apparently low rate of evolution. microRNAs' origin as a regulatory mechanism developed from previous RNAi machinery that was initially used as a defense against exogenous genetic material such as viruses.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Their origin may have permitted the development of morphological innovation, and by making gene expression more specific and 'fine-tunable', permitted the genesis of complex organs and perhaps, ultimately, complex life.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Rapid bursts of morphological innovation are generally associated with a high rate of microRNA accumulation.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] New microRNAs are created in multiple ways.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Individual regions within an miRNA gene face different evolutionary pressures, where regions that are vital for processing and function have higher levels of conservation.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] At this point, a microRNA is rarely lost from an animal's genome, although newer microRNAs (thus presumably non-functional) are frequently lost.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In *Arabidopsis thaliana*, the net flux of miRNA genes has been predicted to be between 1.2 and 3.3 genes per million years.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] This makes them a valuable phylogenetic marker, and they are being looked upon as a possible solution to outstanding phylogenetic problems such as the relationships of arthropods.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] On the other hand, in multiple cases microRNAs correlate poorly with phylogeny, and it is possible that their phylogenetic concordance largely reflects a limited sampling of microRNAs.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] microRNAs feature in the genomes of most eukaryotic organisms, from the brown algae to the animals.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] However, the difference in how these microRNAs function and the way they are processed suggests that microRNAs arose independently in plants and animals.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Focusing on the animals, the genome of *Mnemiopsis leidyi* appears to lack recognizable microRNAs, as well as the nuclear proteins Drosha and Pasha, which are critical to canonical microRNA biogenesis.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] It is the only animal thus far reported to be missing Drosha.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] MicroRNAs play a vital role in the regulation of gene expression in all non-ctenophore animals investigated thus far except for *Trichoplax adhaerens*, the first known member of the phylum Placozoa.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Across all species, in excess of 5000 different miRNAs had been identified by March 2010.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Whilst short RNA sequences (50 – hundreds of base pairs) of a broadly comparable function occur in bacteria, bacteria lack true microRNAs.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] While researchers focused on miRNA expression in physiological and pathological processes, various technical variables related to microRNA isolation emerged.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The stability of stored miRNA samples has been questioned. microRNAs degrade much more easily than mRNAs, partly due to their length, but also because of ubiquitously present RNases.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] This makes it necessary to cool samples on ice and use RNase-free equipment.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] microRNA expression can be quantified in a two-step polymerase chain reaction process of modified RT-PCR followed by quantitative PCR.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The activity of an miRNA can be experimentally inhibited using a locked nucleic acid (LNA) oligo, a Morpholino oligo or a 2'-O-methyl RNA oligo.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] A specific miRNA can be silenced by a complementary antagomir. microRNA maturation can be inhibited at several points by steric-blocking oligos.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The miRNA target site of an mRNA transcript can also be blocked by a steric-blocking oligo.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] For the "in situ" detection of miRNA, LNA or Morpholino probes can be used.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The locked conformation of LNA results in enhanced hybridization properties and increases sensitivity and selectivity, making it ideal for detection of short miRNA.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] High-throughput quantification of miRNAs is error prone, for the larger variance (compared to mRNAs) that comes with methodological problems. mRNA-expression is therefore often analyzed to check for miRNA-effects in their levels (e.g. in).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Databases can be used to pair mRNA- and miRNA-data that predict miRNA-targets based on their base sequence.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] While this is usually done after miRNAs of interest have been detected (e. g. because of high expression levels), ideas for analysis tools that integrate mRNA- and miRNA-expression information have been proposed.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Just as miRNA is involved in the normal functioning of eukaryotic cells, so has dysregulation of miRNA been associated with disease.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] A manually curated, publicly available database, miR2Disease, documents known relationships between miRNA dysregulation and human disease.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] A mutation in the seed region of miR-96 causes hereditary progressive hearing loss.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] A mutation in the seed region of miR-184 causes hereditary keratoconus with anterior polar cataract.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Deletion of the miR-17~92 cluster causes skeletal and growth defects.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The first human disease known to be associated with miRNA deregulation was chronic lymphocytic leukemia.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Many other miRNAs also have links with cancer and accordingly are sometimes referred to as "oncomirs".
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In malignant B cells miRNAs participate in pathways fundamental to B cell development like B-cell receptor (BCR) signalling, B-cell migration/adhesion, cell-cell interactions in immune niches and the production and class-switching of immunoglobulins.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] MiRNAs influence B cell maturation, generation of pre-, marginal zone, follicular, B1, plasma and memory B cells.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Another role for miRNA in cancers is to use their expression level for prognosis.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In NSCLC samples, low miR-324a levels may serve as an indicator of poor survival.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Either high miR-185 or low miR-133b levels may correlate with metastasis and poor survival in colorectal cancer.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Furthermore, specific miRNAs may be associated with certain histological subtypes of colorectal cancer.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] For instance, expression levels of miR-205 and miR-373 have been shown to be increased in mucinous colorectal cancers and mucin-producing Ulcerative Colitis-associated colon cancers, but not in sporadic colonic adenocarcinoma that lack mucinous components.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In-vitro studies suggested that miR-205 and miR-373 may functionally induce different features of mucinous-associated neoplastic progression in intestinal epithelial cells.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Hepatocellular carcinoma cell proliferation may arise from miR-21 interaction with MAP2K3, a tumor repressor gene.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Optimal treatment for cancer involves accurately identifying patients for risk-stratified therapy.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Those with a rapid response to initial treatment may benefit from truncated treatment regimens, showing the value of accurate disease response measures.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Cell-free circulating miRNAs (cimiRNAs) are highly stable in blood, are overexpressed in cancer and are quantifiable within the diagnostic laboratory.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In classical Hodgkin lymphoma, plasma miR-21, miR-494, and miR-1973 are promising disease response biomarkers.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Circulating miRNAs have the potential to assist clinical decision making and aid interpretation of positron emission tomography combined with computerized tomography.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] They can be performed at each consultation to assess disease response and detect relapse.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] MicroRNAs have the potential to be used as tools or targets for treatment of different cancers.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The specific microRNA, miR-506 has been found to work as a tumor antagonist in several studies.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] A significant number of cervical cancer samples were found to have downregulated expression of miR-506.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Additionally, miR-506 works to promote apoptosis of cervical cancer cells, through its direct target hedgehog pathway transcription factor, Gli3.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Many miRNAs can directly target and inhibit cell cycle genes to control cell proliferation.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] A new strategy for tumor treatment is to inhibit tumor cell proliferation by repairing the defective miRNA pathway in tumors.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Cancer is caused by the accumulation of mutations from either DNA damage or uncorrected errors in DNA replication.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Defects in DNA repair cause the accumulation of mutations, which can lead to cancer.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Several genes involved in DNA repair are regulated by microRNAs.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Germline mutations in DNA repair genes cause only 2–5% of colon cancer cases.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] However, altered expression of microRNAs, causing DNA repair deficiencies, are frequently associated with cancers and may be an important causal factor.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Among 68 sporadic colon cancers with reduced expression of the DNA mismatch repair protein MLH1, most were found to be deficient due to epigenetic methylation of the CpG island of the MLH1 gene.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] However, up to 15% of MLH1-deficiencies in sporadic colon cancers appeared to be due to over-expression of the microRNA miR-155, which represses MLH1 expression.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In 29–66% of glioblastomas, DNA repair is deficient due to epigenetic methylation of the MGMT gene, which reduces protein expression of MGMT.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] However, for 28% of glioblastomas, the MGMT protein is deficient, but the MGMT promoter is not methylated.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] In glioblastomas without methylated MGMT promoters, the level of microRNA miR-181d is inversely correlated with protein expression of MGMT and the direct target of miR-181d is the MGMT mRNA 3'UTR (the three prime untranslated region of MGMT mRNA).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Thus, in 28% of glioblastomas, increased expression of miR-181d and reduced expression of DNA repair enzyme MGMT may be a causal factor.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] HMGA proteins (HMGA1a, HMGA1b and HMGA2) are implicated in cancer, and expression of these proteins is regulated by microRNAs.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] HMGA expression is almost undetectable in differentiated adult tissues, but is elevated in many cancers.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] HMGA proteins are polypeptides of ~100 amino acid residues characterized by a modular sequence organization.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] These proteins have three highly positively charged regions, termed AT hooks, that bind the minor groove of AT-rich DNA stretches in specific regions of DNA.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Human neoplasias, including thyroid, prostatic, cervical, colorectal, pancreatic and ovarian carcinomas, show a strong increase of HMGA1a and HMGA1b proteins.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Transgenic mice with HMGA1 targeted to lymphoid cells develop aggressive lymphoma, showing that high HMGA1 expression is associated with cancers and that HMGA1 can act as an oncogene.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] HMGA2 protein specifically targets the promoter of ERCC1, thus reducing expression of this DNA repair gene.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] ERCC1 protein expression was deficient in 100% of 47 evaluated colon cancers (though the extent to which HGMA2 was involved is not known).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Single Nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) can alter the binding of miRNAs on 3'UTRs for example the case of hsa-mir181a and hsa-mir181b on the CDON tumor suppressor gene.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The global role of miRNA function in the heart has been addressed by conditionally inhibiting miRNA maturation in the murine heart.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] This revealed that miRNAs play an essential role during its development. miRNA expression profiling studies demonstrate that expression levels of specific miRNAs change in diseased human hearts, pointing to their involvement in cardiomyopathies.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Furthermore, animal studies on specific miRNAs identified distinct roles for miRNAs both during heart development and under pathological conditions, including the regulation of key factors important for cardiogenesis, the hypertrophic growth response and cardiac conductance.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Another role for miRNA in cardiovascular diseases is to use their expression levels for diagnosis, prognosis or risk stratification. miRNA's in animal models have also been linked to cholesterol metabolism and regulation.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Murine microRNA-712 is a potential biomarker (i.e. predictor) for atherosclerosis, a cardiovascular disease of the arterial wall associated with lipid retention and inflammation.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Non-laminar blood flow also correlates with development of atherosclerosis as mechanosenors of endothelial cells respond to the shear force of disturbed flow (d-flow).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] A number of pro-atherogenic genes including matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs) are upregulated by d-flow, mediating pro-inflammatory and pro-angiogenic signals.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] These findings were observed in ligated carotid arteries of mice to mimic the effects of d-flow.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Within 24 hours, pre-existing immature miR-712 formed mature miR-712 suggesting that miR-712 is flow-sensitive.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Coinciding with these results, miR-712 is also upregulated in endothelial cells exposed to naturally occurring d-flow in the greater curvature of the aortic arch.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Pre-mRNA sequence of miR-712 is generated from the murine ribosomal RN45s gene at the internal transcribed spacer region 2 (ITS2).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] XRN1 is an exonuclease that degrades the ITS2 region during processing of RN45s.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Reduction of XRN1 under d-flowconditions therefore leads to the accumulation of miR-712.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] MiR-712 targets tissue inhibitor of metalloproteinases 3 (TIMP3).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] TIMPs normally regulate activity of matrix metalloproteinases (MMPs) which degrade the extracellular matrix (ECM).
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Arterial ECM is mainly composed of collagen and elastin fibers, providing the structural support and recoil properties of arteries.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] These fibers play a critical role in regulation of vascular inflammation and permeability, which are important in the development of atherosclerosis.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Expressed by endothelial cells, TIMP3 is the only ECM-bound TIMP.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] A decrease in TIMP3 expression results in an increase of ECM degradation in the presence of d-flow.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Consistent with these findings, inhibition of pre-miR712 increases expression of TIMP3 in cells, even when exposed to turbulent flow.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] TIMP3 also decreases the expression of TNFα (a pro-inflammatory regulator) during turbulent flow.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Activity of TNFα in turbulent flow was measured by the expression of TNFα-converting enzyme (TACE) in blood.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] TNFα decreased if miR-712 was inhibited or TIMP3 overexpressed, suggesting that miR-712 and TIMP3 regulate TACE activity in turbulent flow conditions.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Anti-miR-712 effectively suppresses d-flow-induced miR-712 expression and increases TIMP3 expression.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] Anti-miR-712 also inhibits vascular hyperpermeability, thereby significantly reducing atherosclerosis lesion development and immune cell infiltration.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] The human homolog of miR-712 was found on the RN45s homolog gene, which maintains similar miRNAs to mice.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] MiR-205 of humans share similar sequences with miR-712 of mice and is conserved across most vertebrates.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] MiR-205 and miR-712 also share more than 50% of the cell signaling targets, including TIMP3.
[src:rna-interference/microrna] When tested, d-flow decreased the expression of XRN1 in humans as it did in mice endothelial cells, indicating a potentially common role of XRN1 in humans.
