[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] The **RNA-induced silencing complex**, or **RISC**, is a multiprotein complex, specifically a ribonucleoprotein, which functions in gene silencing via a variety of pathways at the transcriptional and translational levels.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] Using single-stranded RNA (ssRNA) fragments, such as microRNA (miRNA), or double-stranded small interfering RNA (siRNA), the complex functions as a key tool in gene regulation.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] The single strand of RNA acts as a template for RISC to recognize complementary messenger RNA (mRNA) transcript.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] Once found, one of the proteins in RISC, Argonaute, activates and cleaves the mRNA.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] This process is called RNA interference (RNAi) and it is found in many eukaryotes; it is a key process in defense against viral infections, as it is triggered by the presence of double-stranded RNA (dsRNA).
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] The biochemical identification of RISC was conducted by Gregory Hannon and his colleagues at the Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] This was only a couple of years after the discovery of RNA interference in 1998 by Andrew Fire and Craig Mello, who shared the 2006 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] Hannon and his colleagues attempted to identify the RNAi mechanisms involved in gene silencing, by dsRNAs, in *Drosophila* cells.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] *Drosophila* S2 cells were transfected with a *lacZ* expression vector to quantify gene expression with β-galactosidase activity.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] Their results showed co-transfection with *lacZ* dsRNA significantly reduced β-galactosidase activity compared to control dsRNA.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] Therefore, dsRNAs control gene expression via sequence complementarity.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] S2 cells were then transfected with *Drosophila* cyclin E dsRNA.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] Cyclin E is an essential gene for cell cycle progression into the S phase.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] Cyclin E dsRNA arrested the cell cycle at the G1 phase (before the S phase).
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] Therefore, RNAi can target endogenous genes.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] In addition, cyclin E dsRNA only diminished cyclin E RNA — a similar result was also shown using dsRNA corresponding to cyclin A which acts in S, G2 and M phases of the cell cycle.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] This shows the characteristic hallmark of RNAi: the reduced levels of mRNAs correspond to the levels of dsRNA added.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] Cells transfected with cyclin E dsRNAs only showed degradation in cyclin E transcripts — the *lacZ* transcripts were stable.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] Conversely, cells transfected with *lacZ* dsRNAs only showed degradation in *lacZ* transcripts and not cyclin E transcripts.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] Their results led Hannon and his colleagues to suggest RNAi degrades target mRNA through a 'sequence-specific nuclease activity'.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] Later Devanand Sarkar and his colleagues Prasanna K.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] Santhekadur and Byoung Kwon Yoo at the Virginia Commonwealth University elucidated the RISC activity and its molecular mechanism in cancer cells and they identified another new component of the RISC, called AEG-1 [47].
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] The RNase III Dicer is a critical member of RISC that initiates the RNA interference process by producing double-stranded siRNA or single-stranded miRNA.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] Enzymatic cleavage of dsRNA within the cell produces the short siRNA fragments of 21-23 nucleotides in length with a two-nucleotide 3' overhang.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] The newly generated miRNA or siRNA act as single-stranded guide sequences for RISC to target mRNA for degradation.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] Major proteins of RISC, Ago2, SND1, and AEG-1, act as crucial contributors to the gene silencing function of the complex.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] RISC uses the guide strand of miRNA or siRNA to target complementary 3'-untranslated regions (3'UTR) of mRNA transcripts via Watson-Crick base pairing, allowing it to regulate gene expression of the mRNA transcript in a number of ways.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] The most understood function of RISC is degradation of target mRNA which reduces the levels of transcript available to be translated by ribosomes.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] The endonucleolytic cleavage of the mRNA complementary to the RISC's guide strand by Argonaute protein is the key to RNAi initiation.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] There are two major pathways of mRNA degradation once cleavage has occurred.
[src:rna-interference/rna-induced-silencing-complex] Both are initiated through degradation of the mRNA's poly(A) tail, resulting in removal of the mRNA's 5' cap.
