[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] These 'secondary' siRNAs are structurally distinct from Dicer-produced siRNAs and appear to be produced by an RNA-dependent RNA polymerase (RdRP).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] MicroRNAs (miRNAs) are genomically encoded non-coding RNAs that help regulate gene expression, particularly during development.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The phenomenon of RNAi, broadly defined, includes the endogenously induced gene silencing effects of miRNAs as well as silencing triggered by foreign dsRNA.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Mature miRNAs are structurally similar to siRNAs produced from exogenous dsRNA, but before reaching maturity, miRNAs must first undergo extensive post-transcriptional modification.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] A miRNA is expressed from a much longer RNA-coding gene as a primary transcript known as a *pri-miRNA* which is processed, in the cell nucleus, to a 70-nucleotide stem-loop structure called a *pre-miRNA* by the microprocessor complex.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This complex consists of an RNase III enzyme called Drosha and a dsRNA-binding protein DGCR8.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The dsRNA portion of this pre-miRNA is bound and cleaved by Dicer to produce the mature miRNA molecule that can be integrated into the RISC complex; thus, miRNA and siRNA share the same downstream cellular machinery.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] First, viral encoded miRNA was described in Epstein–Barr virus (EBV).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Thereafter, an increasing number of microRNAs have been described in viruses.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] VIRmiRNA is a comprehensive catalogue covering viral microRNA, their targets and anti-viral miRNAs (see also VIRmiRNA resource: http://crdd.osdd.net/servers/virmirna/).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] siRNAs derived from long dsRNA precursors differ from miRNAs in that miRNAs, especially those in animals, typically have incomplete base pairing to a target and inhibit the translation of many different mRNAs with similar sequences.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In contrast, siRNAs typically base-pair perfectly and induce mRNA cleavage only in a single, specific target.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In *Drosophila* and *C. elegans*, miRNA and siRNA are processed by distinct Argonaute proteins and Dicer enzymes.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Three prime untranslated regions (3′UTRs) of mRNAs often contain regulatory sequences that post-transcriptionally cause RNAi.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Such 3′-UTRs often contain both binding sites for miRNAs as well as for regulatory proteins.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] By binding to specific sites within the 3′-UTR, miRNAs can decrease gene expression of various mRNAs by either inhibiting translation or directly causing degradation of the transcript.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The 3′-UTR also may have silencer regions that bind repressor proteins that inhibit the expression of a mRNA.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The 3′-UTR often contains microRNA response elements (MREs).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] MREs are sequences to which miRNAs bind.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] These are prevalent motifs within 3′-UTRs.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Among all regulatory motifs within the 3′-UTRs (e.g. including silencer regions), MREs make up about half of the motifs.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] As of 2023, the miRBase web site, an archive of miRNA sequences and annotations, listed 28,645 entries in 271 biologic species.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Of these, 1,917 miRNAs were in annotated human miRNA loci. miRNAs were predicted to have an average of about four hundred target mRNAs (affecting expression of several hundred genes).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Friedman et al. estimate that >45,000 miRNA target sites within human mRNA 3′UTRs are conserved above background levels, and >60% of human protein-coding genes have been under selective pressure to maintain pairing to miRNAs.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Direct experiments show that a single miRNA can reduce the stability of hundreds of unique mRNAs.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Other experiments show that a single miRNA may repress the production of hundreds of proteins, but that this repression often is relatively mild (less than 2-fold).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The effects of miRNA dysregulation of gene expression seem to be important in cancer.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] For instance, in gastrointestinal cancers, nine miRNAs have been identified as epigenetically altered and effective in down regulating DNA repair enzymes.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The effects of miRNA dysregulation of gene expression also seem to be important in neuropsychiatric disorders, such as schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, major depression, Parkinson's disease, Alzheimer's disease and autism spectrum disorders.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This protein only binds long dsRNAs, but the mechanism producing this length specificity is unknown.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This RNA-binding protein then facilitates the transfer of cleaved siRNAs to the RISC complex.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The active components of an RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC) are endonucleases called Argonaute proteins, which cleave the target mRNA strand complementary to their bound siRNA.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] As the fragments produced by Dicer are double-stranded, they could each in theory produce a functional siRNA.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] However, only one of the two strands, which is known as the *guide strand*, binds Argonaute and directs gene silencing.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The other *anti-guide strand* or *passenger strand* is degraded during RISC activation.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Although it was first believed that an ATP-dependent helicase separated these two strands, the process proved to be ATP-independent and performed directly by the protein components of RISC.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] However, an *in vitro* kinetic analysis of RNAi in the presence and absence of ATP showed that ATP may be required to unwind and remove the cleaved mRNA strand from the RISC complex after catalysis.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The guide strand tends to be the one whose 5′ end is less stably paired to its complement, but strand selection is unaffected by the direction in which Dicer cleaves the dsRNA before RISC incorporation.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Instead, the R2D2 protein may serve as the differentiating factor by binding the more-stable 5′ end of the passenger strand.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The structural basis for binding of RNA to the Argonaute protein was examined by X-ray crystallography of the binding domain of an RNA-bound Argonaute.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This site is thought to form a nucleation site for the binding of the siRNA to its mRNA target.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] It is not understood how the activated RISC complex locates complementary mRNAs within the cell.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Although the cleavage process has been proposed to be linked to translation, translation of the mRNA target is not essential for RNAi-mediated degradation.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Indeed, RNAi may be more effective against mRNA targets that are not translated.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Argonaute proteins are localized to specific regions in the cytoplasm called P-bodies (also cytoplasmic bodies or GW bodies), which are regions with high rates of mRNA decay; miRNA activity is also clustered in P-bodies.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Disruption of P-bodies decreases the efficiency of RNAi, suggesting that they are a critical site in the RNAi process.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Components of the RNAi pathway are used in many eukaryotes in the maintenance of the organization and structure of their genomes.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Modification of histones and associated induction of heterochromatin formation serves to downregulate genes pre-transcriptionally; this process is referred to as RNA-induced transcriptional silencing (RITS), and is carried out by a complex of proteins called the RITS complex.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In fission yeast this complex contains Argonaute, a chromodomain protein Chp1, and a protein called Tas3 of unknown function.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] As a consequence, the induction and spread of heterochromatic regions requires the Argonaute and RdRP proteins.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Indeed, deletion of these genes in the fission yeast *S. pombe* disrupts histone methylation and centromere formation, causing slow or stalled anaphase during cell division.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In some cases, similar processes associated with histone modification have been observed to transcriptionally upregulate genes.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The mechanism by which the RITS complex induces heterochromatin formation and organization is not well understood.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Most studies have focused on the mating-type region in fission yeast, which may not be representative of activities in other genomic regions/organisms.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In maintenance of existing heterochromatin regions, RITS forms a complex with siRNAs complementary to the local genes and stably binds local methylated histones, acting co-transcriptionally to degrade any nascent pre-mRNA transcripts that are initiated by RNA polymerase.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The formation of such a heterochromatin region, though not its maintenance, is Dicer-dependent, presumably because Dicer is required to generate the initial complement of siRNAs that target subsequent transcripts.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Heterochromatin maintenance has been suggested to function as a self-reinforcing feedback loop, as new siRNAs are formed from the occasional nascent transcripts by RdRP for incorporation into local RITS complexes.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The relevance of observations from fission yeast mating-type regions and centromeres to mammals is not clear, as heterochromatin maintenance in mammalian cells may be independent of the components of the RNAi pathway.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The type of RNA editing that is most prevalent in higher eukaryotes converts adenosine nucleotides into inosine in dsRNAs via the enzyme adenosine deaminase (ADAR).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] It was originally proposed in 2000 that the RNAi and A→I RNA editing pathways might compete for a common dsRNA substrate.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Some pre-miRNAs do undergo A→I RNA editing and this mechanism may regulate the processing and expression of mature miRNAs.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Furthermore, at least one mammalian ADAR can sequester siRNAs from RNAi pathway components.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Further support for this model comes from studies on ADAR-null *C. elegans* strains indicating that A→I RNA editing may counteract RNAi silencing of endogenous genes and transgenes.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Organisms vary in their ability to take up foreign dsRNA and use it in the RNAi pathway.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The effects of RNAi can be both systemic and heritable in plants and *C. elegans*, although not in *Drosophila* or mammals.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In plants, RNAi is thought to propagate by the transfer of siRNAs between cells through plasmodesmata (channels in the cell walls that enable communication and transport).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Heritability comes from methylation of promoters targeted by RNAi; the new methylation pattern is copied in each new generation of the cell.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This translational effect may be produced by inhibiting the interactions of translation initiation factors with the mRNA's polyadenine tail.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Some eukaryotic protozoa such as *Leishmania major* and *Trypanosoma cruzi* lack the RNAi pathway entirely.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Most or all of the components are also missing in some fungi, most notably the model organism *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The presence of RNAi in other budding yeast species such as *Saccharomyces castellii* and *Candida albicans*, further demonstrates that inducing two RNAi-related proteins from *S. castellii* facilitates RNAi in *S. cerevisiae*.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Gene expression in prokaryotes is influenced by an RNA-based system similar in some respects to RNAi.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Here, RNA-encoding genes control mRNA abundance or translation by producing a complementary RNA that anneals to an mRNA.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] However these regulatory RNAs are not generally considered to be analogous to miRNAs because the Dicer enzyme is not involved.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] It has been suggested that CRISPR interference systems in prokaryotes are analogous to eukaryotic RNAi systems, although none of the protein components are orthologous.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] RNAi is a vital part of the immune response to viruses and other foreign genetic material, especially in plants where it may also prevent the self-propagation of transposons.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Plants such as *Arabidopsis thaliana* express multiple Dicer homologs that are specialized to react differently when the plant is exposed to different viruses.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Even before the RNAi pathway was fully understood, it was known that induced gene silencing in plants could spread throughout the plant in a systemic effect and could be transferred from stock to scion plants via grafting.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This phenomenon has since been recognized as a feature of the plant immune system which allows the entire plant to respond to a virus after an initial localized encounter.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In response, many plant viruses have evolved elaborate mechanisms to suppress the RNAi response.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] These include viral proteins that bind short double-stranded RNA fragments with single-stranded overhang ends, such as those produced by Dicer.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Some plant genomes also express endogenous siRNAs in response to infection by specific types of bacteria.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] These effects may be part of a generalized response to pathogens that downregulates any metabolic process in the host that aids the infection process.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Although animals generally express fewer variants of the Dicer enzyme than plants, RNAi in some animals produces an antiviral response.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In both juvenile and adult *Drosophila*, RNAi is important in antiviral innate immunity and is active against pathogens such as Drosophila X virus.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] A similar role in immunity may operate in *C. elegans*, as Argonaute proteins are upregulated in response to viruses and worms that overexpress components of the RNAi pathway are resistant to viral infection.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The role of RNAi in mammalian innate immunity is poorly understood, and relatively little data is available.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] However, the existence of viruses that encode genes able to suppress the RNAi response in mammalian cells may be evidence in favour of an RNAi-dependent mammalian immune response, although this hypothesis has been challenged as poorly substantiated.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Evidence for the existence of a functional antiviral RNAi pathway in mammalian cells has been presented.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Other functions for RNAi in mammalian viruses also exist, such as miRNAs expressed by the herpes virus that may act as heterochromatin organization triggers to mediate viral latency.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The role of endogenously expressed miRNA in downregulating gene expression was first described in *C. elegans* in 1993.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In plants this function was discovered when the "JAW microRNA" of *Arabidopsis* was shown to be involved in the regulation of several genes that control plant shape.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In plants, the majority of genes regulated by miRNAs are transcription factors; thus miRNA activity is particularly wide-ranging and regulates entire gene networks during development by modulating the expression of key regulatory genes, including transcription factors as well as F-box proteins.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In many organisms, including humans, miRNAs are linked to the formation of tumors and dysregulation of the cell cycle.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Here, miRNAs can function as both oncogenes and tumor suppressors.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Based on parsimony-based phylogenetic analysis, the most recent common ancestor of all eukaryotes most likely already possessed an early RNAi pathway; the absence of the pathway in certain eukaryotes is thought to be a derived characteristic.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This ancestral RNAi system probably contained at least one Dicer-like protein, one Argonaute, one PIWI protein, and an RNA-dependent RNA polymerase that may also have played other cellular roles.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] A large-scale comparative genomics study likewise indicates that the eukaryotic crown group already possessed these components, which may then have had closer functional associations with generalized RNA degradation systems such as the exosome.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This study also suggests that the RNA-binding Argonaute protein family, which is shared among eukaryotes, most archaea, and at least some bacteria (such as *Aquifex aeolicus*), is homologous to and originally evolved from components of the translation initiation system.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Gene knockdown is a method used to reduce the expression of an organism’s specific genes.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This is accomplished by using the naturally occurring process of RNAi.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This gene knockdown technique uses a double-stranded siRNA molecule that is synthesized with a sequence complementary to the gene of interest.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The RNAi cascade begins once the Dicer enzyme starts to process siRNA.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The end result of the process leads to degradation of mRNA and destroys any instructions needed to build certain proteins.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Using this method, researchers are able to decrease (but not completely eliminate) the expression of a targeted gene.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Studying the effects of this decrease in expression may show the physiological role or impact of the targeted gene products.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Extensive efforts in computational biology have been directed toward the design of successful dsRNA reagents that maximize gene knockdown but minimize "off-target" effects.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Off-target effects arise when an introduced RNA has a base sequence that can pair with and thus reduce the expression of multiple genes.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Such problems occur more frequently when the dsRNA contains repetitive sequences.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] It has been estimated from studying the genomes of humans, *C. elegans* and *S. pombe* that about 10% of possible siRNAs have substantial off-target effects.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] A multitude of software tools have been developed implementing algorithms for the design of general mammal-specific, and virus-specific siRNAs that are automatically checked for possible cross-reactivity.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Depending on the organism and experimental system, the exogenous RNA may be a long strand designed to be cleaved by Dicer, or short RNAs designed to serve as siRNA substrates.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In most mammalian cells, shorter RNAs are used because long double-stranded RNA molecules induce the mammalian interferon response, a form of innate immunity that reacts nonspecifically to foreign genetic material.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Mouse oocytes and cells from early mouse embryos lack this reaction to exogenous dsRNA and are therefore a common model system for studying mammalian gene-knockdown effects.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The technique of knocking down genes using RNAi therapeutics has demonstrated success in randomized controlled clinical studies.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] These medications are a growing class of siRNA-based drugs that decrease the expression of proteins encoded by certain genes.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] To date, five RNAi medications have been approved by regulatory authorities in the US and Europe: patisiran (2018), givosiran (2019), lumasiran (2020), inclisiran (2020 in Europe with anticipated US approval in 2021), and vutrisiran (2022).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Patisiran is the first double stranded siRNA-based medication approved in 2018 and developed by Alnylam Pharmaceuticals.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Patisiran uses the RNAi cascade to suppress the gene that codes for TTR (transthryetin).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Mutations in this gene may cause the misfolding of a protein responsible for hereditary ATTR amyloidosis.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] To achieve therapeutic response, patisiran is encased by a lipid nanoparticle membrane that facilitates crossover into the cytoplasm.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Once inside the cell, the siRNA begins processing by the enzyme Dicer.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Patisiran is administered by a healthcare professional through an intravenous infusion with dosing based on body weight.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Warnings and precautions include risk of infusion-related reactions and reduced vitamin A levels (serum).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In 2019, the FDA and EMA approved givosiran for the treatment of adults with acute hepatic porphyria (AHP).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The FDA also granted givosiran a breakthrough therapy designation, priority review designation, and orphan drug designation for the treatment of acute hepatic porphyria (AHP) in November 2019.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] By 2020, givosiran received EMA approval.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Givosiran is an siRNA that breaks down aminolevulinic acid synthase 1 (ALAS1) mRNA in the liver.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Breaking down ALAS1 mRNA prevents toxins (responsible for neurovisceral attacks and AHP disease) such as aminolevulinic acid (ALA) and porphobilinogen (PBG) from accumulating.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] To facilitate entry into the cytoplasm, givosiran uses GalNAc ligands and enters into liver cells.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The medication is administered subcutaneously by a healthcare professional with dosing based on body weight.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Warnings and precautions include risk of anaphylactic reactions, hepatic toxicity, renal toxicity and injection site reactions.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Lumasiran was approved as a siRNA-based medication in 2020 for use in both the European Union and the United States.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This medication is used for the treatment of primary hyperoxaluria type 1 (PH1) in pediatric and adult populations.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The drug is designed to reduce hepatic oxalate production and urinary oxalate levels through RNAi by targeting hydroxyacid oxidase 1 (HAO1) mRNA for breakdown.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Lowering HAO1 enzyme levels reduces the oxidation of glycolate to glyoxylate (which is a substrate for oxalate).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Lumasiran is administered subcutaneously by a healthcare professional with dosing based on body weight.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Data from randomized controlled clinical trials indicate that the most common adverse reaction that was reported was injection site reactions.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] These reactions were mild and were present in 38 percent of patients treated with lumasiran.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In 2022, the FDA and EMA approved vutrisiran for the treatment of adults with hereditary transthyretin mediated amyloidosis with polyneuropathy stage 1 or 2.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Vutrisiran is designed to break down the mRNA that codes for transthyretin.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Other investigational drugs using RNAi that are being developed by pharmaceutical companies such as Arrowhead Pharmaceuticals, Dicerna, Alnylam Pharmaceuticals, Amgen, and Sylentis.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] These medications cover a variety of targets via RNAi and diseases.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Currently, both miRNA and SiRNA are currently chemically synthesized and so, are legally categorized inside EU and in USA as "simple" medicinal products.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] But as bioengineered siRNA (BERAs) are in development, these would be classified as biological medicinal products, at least in EU.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The development of the BERAs technology raises the question of the categorization of drugs having the same mechanism of action but being produced chemically or biologically.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This lack of consistency should be addressed.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] To achieve the clinical potential of RNAi, siRNA must be efficiently transported to the cells of target tissues.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] However, there are various barriers that must be fixed before it can be used clinically.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] For example, "naked" siRNA is susceptible to several obstacles that reduce its therapeutic efficacy.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Additionally, once siRNA has entered the bloodstream, naked RNA can be degraded by serum nucleases and can stimulate the innate immune system.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Due to its size and highly polyanionic (containing negative charges at several sites) nature, unmodified siRNA molecules cannot readily enter the cells through the cell membrane.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Therefore, artificial or nanoparticle encapsulated siRNA must be used.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] If siRNA is transferred across the cell membrane, unintended toxicities can occur if therapeutic doses are not optimized, and siRNAs can exhibit off-target effects (e.g. unintended downregulation of genes with partial sequence complementarity).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Even after entering the cells, repeated dosing is required since their effects are diluted at each cell division.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In response to these potential issues and barriers, two approaches help facilitate siRNA delivery to target cells: lipid nanoparticles and conjugates.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Lipid nanoparticles (LNPs) are based on liposome-like structures that are typically made of an aqueous center surrounded by a lipid shell.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] A subset of liposomal structures used for delivery drugs to tissues rest in large unilamellar vesicles (LUVs) which may be 100 nm in size.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] LNP delivery mechanisms have become an increasing source of encasing nucleic acids and may include plasmids, CRISPR and mRNA.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The first approved use of lipid nanoparticles as a drug delivery mechanism began in 2018 with the siRNA drug patisiran, developed by Alnylam Pharmaceuticals.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Dicerna Pharmaceuticals, Persomics, Sanofi and Sirna Therapeutics also worked to bring RNAi therapies to market.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Other recent applications include two FDA approved COVID-19 vaccines: mRNA-1273, developed by Moderna. and BNT162b, developed by a collaboration between Pfizer and BioNtech.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] These two vaccines use lipid nanoparticles to deliver antigen mRNA.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In December 2020, Novartis announced that positive results from phase III efficacy studies deemed inclisiran was a treatment for heterozygous familial hypercholesterolemia (HeFH) and atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease (ASCVD).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In addition to LNPs, RNAi therapeutics have targeted delivery through siRNA conjugates (e.g., GalNAc, carbohydrates, peptides, aptamers, antibodies).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Therapeutics using siRNA conjugates have been developed for rare or genetic diseases such as acute hepatic porphyria (AHP), hemophilia, primary hyperoxaluria (PH) and hereditary ATTR amyloidosis as well as other cardiometabolic diseases such as hypertension and non-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Antiviral treatment is one of the earliest proposed RNAi-based medical applications, and two different types have been developed.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Many studies have shown that targeting viral RNAs can suppress the replication of numerous viruses, including HIV, HPV, hepatitis A, hepatitis B, influenza virus, respiratory syncytial virus (RSV), SARS coronavirus (SARS-CoV), adenovirus and measles virus.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The other strategy is to block the initial viral entries by targeting the host cell genes.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] For example, suppression of chemokine receptors (CXCR4 and CCR5) on host cells can prevent HIV viral entry.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] While traditional chemotherapy can effectively kill cancer cells, lack of specificity for discriminating normal cells and cancer cells in these treatments usually cause severe side effects.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Numerous studies have demonstrated that RNAi can provide a more specific approach to inhibit tumor growth by targeting cancer-related genes (i.e., oncogene).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] It has also been proposed that RNAi can enhance the sensitivity of cancer cells to chemotherapeutic agents, providing a combinatorial therapeutic approach with chemotherapy.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Another potential RNAi-based treatment is to inhibit cell invasion and migration.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Compared with chemotherapy or other anti-cancer drugs, there are a lot of advantages of siRNA drug.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] SiRNA acts on the post-transcriptional stage of gene expression, so it does not modify or change DNA in a deleterious effect.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] SiRNA can also be used to produce a specific response in a certain type of way, such as by downgrading suppression of gene expression.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In a single cancer cell, siRNA can cause dramatic suppression of gene expression with just several copies.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This happens by silencing cancer-promoting genes with RNAi, as well as targeting an mRNA sequence.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] RNAi drugs treat cancer by silencing certain cancer promoting genes.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This is done by complementing the cancer genes with the RNAi, such as keeping the mRNA sequences in accordance with the RNAi drug.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Ideally, RNAi is should be injected and/or chemically modified so the RNAi can reach cancer cells more efficiently.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] RNAi uptake and regulation is controlled by the kidneys.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] RNAi strategies also show potential for treating neurodegenerative diseases.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Studies in cells and in mouse have shown that specifically targeting Amyloid beta-producing genes (e.g.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] BACE1 and APP) by RNAi can significantly reduced the amount of Aβ peptide which is correlated with the cause of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In addition, this silencing-based approaches also provide promising results in treatment of Parkinson's disease and Polyglutamine disease.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The human immune system is divided into two separate branches: the innate immune system and the adaptive immune system.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The innate immune system is the first defense against infection and responds to pathogens in a generic fashion.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] On the other hand, the adaptive immune system, a system that was evolved later than the innate, is composed mainly of highly specialized B and T cells that are trained to react to specific portions of pathogenic molecules.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The challenge between old pathogens and new has helped create a system of guarded cells and particles that are called safe framework.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This framework has given humans an army of systems that search out and destroy invader particles, such as pathogens, microscopic organisms, parasites, and infections.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The mammalian safe framework has developed to incorporate siRNA as a tool to indicate viral contamination, which has allowed siRNA is create an intense innate immune response.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] siRNA is controlled by the innate immune system, which can be divided into the acute inflammatory responses and antiviral responses.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The inflammatory response is created with signals from small signaling molecules, or cytokines.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] These include interleukin-1 (IL-1), interleukin-6 (IL-6), interleukin-12 (IL-12) and tumor necrosis factor α (TNF-α).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The innate immune system generates inflammation and antiviral responses, which cause the release pattern recognition receptors (PRRs).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] These receptors help in labeling which pathogens are viruses, fungi, or bacteria.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Moreover, the importance of siRNA and the innate immune system is to include more PRRs to help recognize different RNA structures.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This makes it more likely for the siRNA to cause an immunostimulant response in the event of the pathogen.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] RNAi has been used for a variety of agricultural applications including genetically engineered crops and insecticides.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The use of the RNAi pathway has developed numerous products such as foods like Arctic apples, nicotine-free tobacco, decaffeinated coffee, nutrient fortified vegetation and hypoallergenic crops.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The emerging use of RNAi has the potential to develop many other products for future use.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] RNAi has been used to genetically engineer plants to produce lower levels of natural plant toxins.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Such techniques take advantage of the stable and heritable RNAi phenotype in plant stocks.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Cotton seeds are rich in dietary protein but naturally contain the toxic terpenoid product gossypol, making them unsuitable for human consumption.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] RNAi has been used to produce cotton stocks whose seeds contain reduced levels of delta-cadinene synthase, a key enzyme in gossypol production, without affecting the enzyme's production in other parts of the plant, where gossypol is itself important in preventing damage from plant pests.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Development efforts have successfully reduced the levels of allergens in tomato plants and fortification of plants such as tomatoes with dietary antioxidants.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] RNAi silencing of alpha-amylase have also been used to decrease Aspergillus flavus fungal growth in maize which would have otherwise contaminated the kernels with dangerous aflatoxins.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Silencing lachrymatory factor synthase in onions has produced tearless onions, and RNAi has been used in BP1 genes in rapeseeds to improve photosynthesis.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] SBEIIa and SBEIIb genes in wheat have been targeted in wheat in order to produce higher levels of amylose in order to improve bowel function, and Travella et al.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] 2006 employed RNAi for functional genomics an investigation of hexaploid bread races, while virus-induced gene silencing (VIGS, a subtype of RNAi) was used by Scofield et al.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] 2005 to investigate the mechanism of resistance provided by *Lr21* against wheat leaf rust in hexaploid wheat.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] RNAi is under development as an insecticide, employing multiple approaches, including genetic engineering and topical application.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Cells in the midgut of some insects take up the dsRNA molecules in the process referred to as environmental RNAi.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] In some insects the effect is systemic as the signal spreads throughout the insect's body (referred to as systemic RNAi).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Animals exposed to RNAi at doses millions of times higher than anticipated human exposure levels show no adverse effects.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] RNAi has varying effects in different species of Lepidoptera (butterflies and moths).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Transgenic crops have been made to express dsRNA, carefully chosen to silence crucial genes in target pests.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] These dsRNAs are designed to affect only insects that express specific gene sequences.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] As a proof of principle, in 2009 a study showed RNAs that could kill any one of four fruit fly species while not harming the other three.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Alternatively dsRNA can be supplied without genetic engineering.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] One approach is to add them to irrigation water.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The molecules are absorbed into the plants' vascular system and poison insects feeding on them.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Another approach involves spraying dsRNA like a conventional pesticide.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This would allow faster adaptation to resistance.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Such approaches would require low cost sources of dsRNAs that do not currently exist.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Approaches to the design of genome-wide RNAi libraries can require more sophistication than the design of a single siRNA for a defined set of experimental conditions.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Artificial neural networks are frequently used to design siRNA libraries and to predict their likely efficiency at gene knockdown.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Mass genomic screening is widely seen as a promising method for genome annotation and has triggered the development of high-throughput screening methods based on microarrays.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Genome-scale RNAi research relies on high-throughput screening (HTS) technology.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] RNAi HTS technology allows genome-wide loss-of-function screening and is broadly used in the identification of genes associated with specific phenotypes.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] This technology has been hailed as a potential second genomics wave, following the first genomics wave of gene expression microarray and single nucleotide polymorphism discovery platforms.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] One major advantage of genome-scale RNAi screening is its ability to simultaneously interrogate thousands of genes.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] With the ability to generate a large amount of data per experiment, genome-scale RNAi screening has led to an explosion of data generation rates.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] Exploiting such large data sets is a fundamental challenge, requiring suitable statistics/bioinformatics methods.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p01] The basic process of cell-based RNAi screening includes the choice of an RNAi library, robust and stable cell types, transfection with RNAi agents, treatment/incubation, signal detection, analysis and identification of important genes or therapeutical targets.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] The process of RNAi was referred to as "co-suppression" and "quelling" when observed prior to the knowledge of an RNA-related mechanism.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] The discovery of RNAi was preceded first by observations of transcriptional inhibition by antisense RNA expressed in transgenic plants, and more directly by reports of unexpected outcomes in experiments performed by plant scientists in the United States and the Netherlands in the early 1990s.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] In an attempt to alter flower colors in petunias, researchers introduced additional copies of a gene encoding chalcone synthase, a key enzyme for flower pigmentation into petunia plants of normally pink or violet flower color.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] Another early observation of RNAi came from a study of the fungus *Neurospora crassa*, although it was not immediately recognized as related.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] Further investigation of the phenomenon in plants indicated that the downregulation was due to post-transcriptional inhibition of gene expression via an increased rate of mRNA degradation.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] This phenomenon was called *co-suppression of gene expression*, but the molecular mechanism remained unknown.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] Not long after, plant virologists working on improving plant resistance to viral diseases observed a similar unexpected phenomenon.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] While it was known that plants expressing virus-specific proteins showed enhanced tolerance or resistance to viral infection, it was not expected that plants carrying only short, non-coding regions of viral RNA sequences would show similar levels of protection.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] Researchers believed that viral RNA produced by transgenes could also inhibit viral replication.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] The reverse experiment, in which short sequences of plant genes were introduced into viruses, showed that the targeted gene was suppressed in an infected plant.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] After these initial observations in plants, laboratories searched for this phenomenon in other organisms.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] The first instance of RNA silencing in animals was documented in 1996, when Guo and Kemphues observed that, by introducing sense and antisense RNA to par-1 mRNA in *Caenorhabditis elegans* caused degradation of the par-1 message.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] It was thought that this degradation was triggered by single-stranded RNA (ssRNA), but two years later, in 1998, Fire and Mello discovered that this ability to silence the par-1 gene expression was actually triggered by double-stranded RNA (dsRNA).
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] Mello and Andrew Fire's 1998 *Nature* paper reported a potent gene silencing effect after injecting double stranded RNA into *C. elegans*.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] In investigating the regulation of muscle protein production, they observed that neither mRNA nor antisense RNA injections had an effect on protein production, but double-stranded RNA successfully silenced the targeted gene.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] As a result of this work, they coined the term *RNAi*.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] This discovery represented the first identification of the causative agent for the phenomenon.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] Fire and Mello were awarded the 2006 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] Just after Fire and Mello's ground-breaking discovery, Elbashir et al. discovered, by using synthetically made siRNA, it was possible to target the silencing of specific sequences in a gene, rather than silencing the entire gene.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] Only a year later, McCaffrey and colleagues demonstrated that this sequence-specific silencing had therapeutic applications by targeting a sequence from the Hepatitis C virus in transgenic mice.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] Since then, multiple researchers have been attempting to expand the therapeutic applications of RNAi, specifically looking to target genes that cause various types of cancer.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] By 2006, the first applications to reach clinical trials were in the treatment of macular degeneration and respiratory syncytial virus.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] Four years later the first-in-human Phase I clinical trial was started, using a nanoparticle delivery system to target solid tumors.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] The FDA approved the first siRNA-based drug (patisiran) in 2018.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] Givosiran and lumasiran later won FDA approval for the treatment of AHP and PH1 in 2019 and 2020, respectively.
[src:rna-interference/rna-interference-p02] Inclisiran received EMA approval in 2020 for the treatment of high cholesterol and is currently under review by the FDA.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Naturally occurring siRNAs have a well-defined structure that is a short (usually 20 to 24-bp) double-stranded RNA (dsRNA) with phosphorylated 5' ends and hydroxylated 3' ends with two overhanging nucleotides.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] As of 2001, it had been suggested that an enzyme referred to as Dicer catalyzed "the initiation step of RNA interference" (production of siRNAs from long dsRNAs and small hairpin RNAs).
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] siRNAs can also be introduced into cells by transfection.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Since, in principle, any gene can be knocked down by a synthetic siRNA with a complementary sequence, siRNAs are an important tool for validating gene function and drug targeting in the "post-genomic era".
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] In 1998, Andrew Fire at Carnegie Institution for Science in Washington DC and Craig Mello at University of Massachusetts in Worcester discovered the RNAi mechanism while working on the gene expression in the nematode, *Caenorhabditis elegans*.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The two won the Nobel prize for their research with RNAi in 2006. siRNA and its role in post-transcriptional gene silencing (PTGS) was discovered in plants by David Baulcombe's group at the Sainsbury Laboratory in Norwich, England, a discovery reported in *Science* in 1999.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Thomas Tuschl and colleagues soon reported in *Nature* that synthetic siRNAs could induce RNAi in mammalian cells.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] These discoveries led to a surge in interest in harnessing RNAi for biomedical research and drug development.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] As of 2017, human applications of siRNA had faced significant roadblocks to their success, one of these being "off-targeting".
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] As that decade came to a close, the possibility that these therapies could trigger innate immunity had been discussed.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] As of 2019, animal models had not been successful in accurately representing the extent of this response in humans; hence, studying the effects of siRNA therapies has been a challenge.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] As of 2020, siRNA therapies had been approved (e.g., by the FDA in the U.S.), and new methods had been established to overcome challenges; this includes approved, commercially available therapies, several further that are in pipelines seeking approval, and others earlier in development.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Once siRNA enters the cell it gets incorporated into other proteins to form the RISC.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Once the siRNA is part of the RISC complex, the siRNA is unwound to form single stranded siRNA.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Once the single stranded siRNA (part of the RISC complex) binds to its target mRNA, it induces mRNA cleavage.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The mRNA is now cut and recognized as abnormal by the cell.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] This causes degradation of the mRNA and in turn no translation of the mRNA into amino acids and then proteins.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Thus silencing the gene that encodes that mRNA.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Gene knockdown by transfection of exogenous siRNA is only transient, especially in rapidly dividing cells.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] This may be overcome by creating an expression vector for the siRNA.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The siRNA sequence is modified to introduce a short loop between the two strands.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The resulting transcript is a short hairpin RNA (shRNA), which can be processed into a functional siRNA by Dicer in its usual fashion.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Typical transcription cassettes use an RNA polymerase III promoter (e.g., U6 or H1) to direct the transcription of small nuclear RNAs (snRNAs, where U6 is involved in RNA splicing; H1 is the RNase component of human RNase P).
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] It is theorized that the resulting siRNA transcript is then processed by Dicer.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The gene knockdown efficiency can also be improved by using cell squeezing.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The activity of siRNAs in RNAi is largely dependent on its binding ability to the RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC).
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Binding of the duplex siRNA to RISC is followed by unwinding and cleavage of the sense strand with endonucleases.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The remaining anti-sense strand-RISC complex can then bind to target mRNAs for initiating transcriptional silencing.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] In addition to their role in RNAi, siRNAs can also activate gene expression, a phenomenon termed "RNA activation" or RNAa.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] This was first observed when synthetic siRNAs, termed "small activating RNA" (saRNA), targeting gene promoters were found to induce potent transcriptional activation of target genes.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] RNAa has been demonstrated to be a conserved mechanism, observed across species from insects, *C. elegans*, and plants, to mammals (including humans).
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The mechanism of RNAa involves the targeting of promoter regions by saRNAs, leading to the recruitment of transcriptional machinery and epigenetic changes that promote gene expression.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] This process often involves the RNA-induced transcriptional activation (RITA) complex, which includes Argonaute proteins (particularly Ago2), RNA helicase A (RHA), and CTR9.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Endogenous miRNAs can also mediate RNAa, expanding the regulatory roles of these small RNAs beyond gene silencing.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Several saRNA-based therapeutics are currently in clinical development.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] MTL-CEBPA, developed by MiNA Therapeutics, targets the *CEBPA* gene and is in Phase II trials for liver cancer.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] RAG-01, developed by Ractigen Therapeutics, targets the *p21* gene and is in Phase I trials for non-muscle invasive bladder cancer (NMIBC).
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] These clinical trials represent a significant step towards translating the RNAa phenomenon into novel therapeutic strategies.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Richard Carthew et al. state in their 2004 study of siRNA/miRNA silencing pathways in *Drosophila* that siRNA-induced post transcriptional gene silencing is initiated by the assembly of the RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC).
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] RISC silences expression of certain genes by cleaving the mRNA molecules coding those genes.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Then, in a perspective from 2009, the view is offered that "siRNA scans for and directs RISC" to perfectly complementary sequence on the mRNA molecules.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The cleavage of the mRNA molecules is thought to be catalyzed by the Piwi domain of Argonaute proteins of the RISC; the mRNA molecule is then cut precisely by cleaving the phosphodiester bond between the target nucleotides which are paired to siRNA residues 10 and 11, counting from the 5'end.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Dissociation of the target mRNA strand from RISC after the cleavage allow more mRNA to be silenced; this dissociation process is likely to be promoted by extrinsic factors driven by ATP hydrolysis.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Sometimes, cleavage of the target mRNA molecule does not occur.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] In some cases, the endonucleolytic cleavage of the phosphodiester backbone may be suppressed by mismatches of siRNA and target mRNA near the cleaving site.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Other times, the Argonaute proteins of the RISC lack endonuclease activity even when the target mRNA and siRNA are perfectly paired.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] In such cases, gene expression will be silenced by an miRNA-induced mechanism instead.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Piwi-interacting RNAs (piRNAs) are a recently discovered class of small non-coding RNAs (ncRNAs) with a length of 21-35 nucleotides.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] They play a role in gene expression regulation, transposon silencing, and viral infection inhibition.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Many model organism, such as plants (Arabidopsis thaliana), yeast (Saccharomyces cerevisiae), flies (Drosophila melanogaster) and worms (C. elegans), have been used to study small non coding RNA-directed Transcriptional gene silencing.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] In human cell, RNA-directed transcriptional gene silencing was observed a decade ago when exogenous siRNAs silenced a transgenic elongation factor 1 α promoter driving a Green Fluorescent Protein (GFP) reporter gene.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The main mechanisms of transcriptional gene silencing (TGS) involving the RNAi machinery include DNA methylation, histone post-translational modifications, and subsequent chromatin remodeling around the target gene into a heterochromatic state.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] SiRNAs can be incorporated into a RNA-induced transcriptional silencing (RITS) complex.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] An active RITS complex will trigger the formation of heterochromatin around DNA matching the siRNA, effectively silencing the genes in that region of the DNA.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] One of the potent applications of siRNAs is the ability to distinguish the target versus non-target sequence with a single-nucleotide difference.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] This approach has been considered as therapeutically crucial for the silencing dominant gain-of-function (GOF) disorders, where mutant allele causing disease is differed from wt-allele by a single nucleotide (nt).
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] These types of siRNAs with the capability to distinguish a single-nt difference, are termed as, allele-specific siRNAs.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] ASP-RNAi is an innovative category of RNAi with the objective of suppressing the dominant mutant allele while sparing expression of the corresponding normal allele with the specificity of single-nucleotide differences between the two.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] ASP-siRNAs are potentially a novel and better remedial alternative for the treatment of autosomal dominant genetic disorders especially in cases where wild-type allele expression is crucial for organism survival such as Huntington disease (HD),DYT1 dystonia (Gonzalez-Alegre et al.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] 2011), Parkinson's disease (PD) (Takahashi et al.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] 2015), amyloid lateral sclerosis (ALS) (Schwarz et al.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] 2006), and Machado–Joseph disease (Alves et al.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Their therapeutic potential has also been assessed for various skin disorders like epidermolysis bullosa simplex (Atkinson et al.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] 2011), epidermolytic palmoplantar keratoderma (EPPK) (Lyu et al.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] 2016), and lattice corneal dystrophy type I (LCDI) (Courtney et al.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] RNAi intersects with a number of other pathways; as of 2010 it was not surprising that on occasion, nonspecific effects are triggered by the experimental introduction of an siRNA.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] When a mammalian cell encounters a double-stranded RNA such as an siRNA, it may mistake it as a viral by-product and mount an immune response.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Furthermore, because structurally related microRNAs modulate gene expression largely via incomplete complementarity base pair interactions with a target mRNA, the introduction of an siRNA may cause unintended off-targeting.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Chemical modifications of siRNA may alter the thermodynamic properties that also result in a loss of single nucleotide specificity.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Introduction of too many siRNA can result in nonspecific events due to activation of innate immune responses.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Most evidence to date suggests that this is probably due to activation of the dsRNA sensor PKR, although retinoic acid-inducible gene I (RIG-I) may also be involved.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The induction of cytokines via toll-like receptor 7 (TLR7) has also been described.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Chemical modification of siRNA is employed to reduce in the activation of the innate immune response for gene function and therapeutic applications.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] One promising method of reducing the nonspecific effects is to convert the siRNA into a microRNA.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] MicroRNAs occur naturally, and by harnessing this endogenous pathway it should be possible to achieve similar gene knockdown at comparatively low concentrations of resulting siRNAs, to minimize nonspecific effects.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Off-targeting is another challenge to the use of siRNAs as a gene knockdown tool.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Here, genes with incomplete complementarity are inadvertently downregulated by the siRNA (in effect, the siRNA acts as a miRNA), leading to problems in data interpretation and potential toxicity.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] This, however, can be partly addressed by designing appropriate control experiments, and siRNA design algorithms are currently being developed to produce siRNAs free from off-targeting.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Genome-wide expression analysis, e.g., by microarray technology, can then be used to verify this and further refine the algorithms.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] A 2006 paper from the laboratory of Anastasia Khvorova implicates 6- or 7-basepair-long stretches from position 2 onward in the siRNA matching with 3'UTR regions in off-targeted genes.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The tool of siRNA off-target predition is available at http://crdd.osdd.net/servers/aspsirna/asptar.php and published as ASPsiRNA resource.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Plain RNAs may be poor immunogens, but antibodies can easily be created against RNA-protein complexes.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Many autoimmune diseases see these types of antibodies.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] There haven't yet been reports of antibodies against siRNA bound to proteins.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Some methods for siRNA delivery adjoin polyethylene glycol (PEG) to the oligonucleotide reducing excretion and improving circulating half-life.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] However recently a large Phase III trial of PEGylated RNA aptamer against factor IX had to be discontinued by Regado Biosciences because of a severe anaphylactic reaction to the PEG part of the RNA.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] This reaction led to death in some cases and raises significant concerns about siRNA delivery when PEGylated oligonucleotides are involved.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] siRNAs transfection into cells typically lowers the expression of many genes, however, the upregulation of genes is also observed.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The upregulation of gene expression can partially be explained by the predicted gene targets of endogenous miRNAs.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Computational analyses of more than 150 siRNA transfection experiments support a model where exogenous siRNAs can saturate the endogenous RNAi machinery, resulting in the de-repression of endogenous miRNA-regulated genes.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] siRNAs have been chemically modified to enhance their therapeutic properties, Short interfering RNA (siRNA) must be delivered to the site of action in the cells of target tissues in order for RNAi to fulfill its therapeutic promise.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] A detailed database of all such chemical modifications is manually curated as siRNAmod in scientific literature.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Chemical modification of siRNA can also inadvertently result in loss of single-nucleotide specificity.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Given the ability to knock down, in essence, any gene of interest, RNAi via siRNAs has generated a great deal of interest in both basic and applied biology.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] One of the biggest challenges to siRNA and RNAi based therapeutics is intracellular delivery. siRNA also has weak stability and pharmacokinetic behavior.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Delivery of siRNA via nanoparticles has shown promise. siRNA oligos in vivo are vulnerable to degradation by plasma and tissue endonucleases and exonucleases and have shown only mild effectiveness in localized delivery sites, such as the human eye.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Delivering pure DNA to target organisms is challenging because its large size and structure prevents it from diffusing readily across membranes. siRNA oligos circumvent this problem due to their small size of 21-23 oligos.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] This allows delivery via nano-scale delivery vehicles called nanovectors.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] A good nanovector for siRNA delivery should protect siRNA from degradation, enrich siRNA in the target organ and facilitate the cellular uptake of siRNA.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The three main groups of siRNA nanovectors are: lipid based, non-lipid organic-based, and inorganic.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Lipid based nanovectors are excellent for delivering siRNA to solid tumors, but other cancers may require different non-lipid based organic nanovectors such as cyclodextrin based nanoparticles.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] siRNAs delivered via lipid based nanoparticles have been shown to have therapeutic potential for central nervous system (CNS) disorders.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] A huge difficulty in siRNA delivery is the problem of off-targeting.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Since genes are read in both directions, there exists a possibility that even if the intended antisense siRNA strand is read and knocks out the target mRNA, the sense siRNA strand may target another protein involved in another function.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Phase I results of the first two therapeutic RNAi trials (indicated for age-related macular degeneration, aka AMD) reported at the end of 2005 that siRNAs are well tolerated and have suitable pharmacokinetic properties.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] In a phase 1 clinical trial, 41 patients with advanced cancer metastasised to liver were administered RNAi delivered through lipid nanoparticles.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The RNAi targeted two genes encoding key proteins in the growth of the cancer cells, vascular endothelial growth factor, (VEGF), and kinesin spindle protein (KSP).
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The results showed clinical benefits, with the cancer either stabilized after six months, or regression of metastasis in some of the patients.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Pharmacodynamic analysis of biopsy samples from the patients revealed the presence of the RNAi constructs in the samples, proving that the molecules reached the intended target.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Proof of concept trials have indicated that Ebola-targeted siRNAs may be effective as post-exposure prophylaxis in humans, with 100% of non-human primates surviving a lethal dose of Zaire Ebolavirus, the most lethal strain.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Currently, SiRNA are currently chemically synthesized and so, are legally categorized inside EU and in USA as simple medicinal products.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] There is great potential for RNA interference (RNAi) to be used therapeutically to reversibly silence any gene.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] For RNAi to realize its therapeutic potential, small interfering RNA (siRNA) must be delivered to the site of action in the cells of target tissues.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] But finding safe and efficient delivery mechanisms is a major obstacle to achieving the full potential of siRNA-based therapies.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Unmodified siRNA is unstable in the bloodstream, has the potential to cause immunogenicity, and has difficulty readily navigating cell membranes.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] As a result, chemical alterations and/or delivery tools are needed to safely transfer siRNA to its site of action.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] There are three main techniques of delivery for siRNA that differ on efficiency and toxicity.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] In this technique siRNA first must be designed against the target gene.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Once the siRNA is configured against the gene it has to be effectively delivered through a transfection protocol.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Delivery is usually done by cationic liposomes, polymer nanoparticles, and lipid conjugation.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] This method is advantageous because it can deliver siRNA to most types of cells, has high efficiency and reproducibility, and is offered commercially.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The most common commercial reagents for transfection of siRNA are Lipofectamine and Neon Transfection.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] However, it is not compatible with all cell types and has low in vivo efficiency.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Electrical pulses are also used to intracellularly deliver siRNA into cells.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The cell membrane is made of phospholipids which makes it susceptible to an electric field.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] When quick but powerful electrical pulses are initiated, the lipid molecules reorient themselves, while undergoing thermal phase transitions because of heating.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] This results in hydrophilic pores and localized perturbations in the lipid bilayer of the cell membrane, and temporary loss of semipermeability.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] This allows for the escape of intracellular contents (ions, metabolites, etc.) as well as for the uptake of drugs, molecular probes, and nucleic acids.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] For cells that are difficult to transfect, electroporation is advantageous; however, cell death is more likely under this technique.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The method has been used to deliver siRNA targeting VEGF into the xenografted tumors in nude mice, which resulted in a significant suppression of tumor growth.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The gene silencing effects of transfected designed siRNA are generally transient, but this difficulty can be overcome through an RNAi approach.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Delivering this siRNA from DNA templates can be done through several recombinant viral vectors based on retrovirus, adeno-associated virus, adenovirus, and lentivirus.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] As of primary research work in 2006, the latter virus was the most efficient for stable delivery of siRNA to target cells, as it could be used to transduce nondividing cells, as well as to directly target the nucleus.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] These specific viral vectors have been synthesized to effectively facilitate siRNA that is not viable for transfection into cells.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] In some cases synthetic viral vectors can integrate siRNA into the cell genome, which allows for stable expression of siRNA and long-term gene knockdown.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] This technique is advantageous because it is an *in vivo* method, and can be effective for difficult to transfect cells.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] However, problems arise because it can trigger antiviral responses in some cell types, leading to mutagenic and immunogenic effects.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] This method has been shown to have potential for use in gene silencing of the central nervous system genes, e.g., in the treatment of Huntington's disease.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] A decade after the discovery of RNAi mechanism in 1993, the pharmaceutical sector heavily invested in the research and development of siRNA therapy.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] There are several advantages that this therapy has over small molecules and antibodies.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] It can be administered quarterly or every six months.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Another advantage is that, unlike small molecule and monoclonal antibodies that need to recognize specific conformation of a protein, siRNA functions by Watson-Crick basepairing with mRNA.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Therefore, any target molecule that needs to be treated with high affinity and specificity can be selected if the right nucleotide sequence is available.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] One of the biggest challenges researchers needed to overcome was the identification and establishment of a delivery system through which the therapies would enter the body.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] And that the immune system often mistakes the RNAi therapies as remnants of infectious agents, which can trigger an immune response.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Animal models did not accurately represent the degree of immune response that was seen in humans and despite the promise in the treatment investors divested away from RNAi.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] However, there were a few companies that continued with the development of RNAi therapy for humans.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Alnylam Pharmaceuticals, Sirna Therapeutics and Dicerna Pharmaceuticals are few of the companies still working on bringing RNAi therapies to market.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] It was learned that almost all siRNA therapies administered in the bloodstream accumulated in the liver.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] That is why most of the early drug targets were diseases that affected the liver.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Repeated developmental work also shed light on improving the chemical composition of the RNA molecule to reduce the immune response, subsequently causing little to no side effects.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Listed below are some of approved therapies or therapies in pipeline.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] In 2018, Alnylam Pharmaceuticals became the first company to have a siRNA therapy approved by the FDA.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Onpattro (patisiran) was approved for the treatment of polyneuropathy of hereditary transthyretin-mediated (hATTR) amyloidosis in adults. hATTR is a rare, progressively debilitating condition.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] During hATTR amyloidosis, misfolded transthyretin (TTR) protein is deposited in the extracellular space.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Under typical folding conditions, TTR tetramers are made up of four monomers.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Hereditary ATTR amyloidosis is caused by a fault or mutation in the transthyretin (TTR) gene which is inherited.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Changing just one amino-acid changes the tetrameric transthyretin proteins, resulting in unstable tetrameric transthyretin protein that aggregates in monomers and forms insoluble extracellular amyloid deposits.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Amyloid buildup in various organ systems causes cardiomyopathy, polyneuropathy, gastrointestinal dysfunction.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] To deliver the drug directly to the liver, siRNA is encased in a lipid nanoparticle.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The siRNA molecule halts the production of amyloid proteins by interfering with the RNA production of abnormal TTR proteins.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] This prevents the accumulation of these proteins in different organs of the body and helps the patients manage this disease.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Traditionally, liver transplantation has been the standard treatment for hereditary transthyretin amyloidosis, however its effectiveness may be limited by the persistent deposition of wild-type transthyretin amyloid after transplantation.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] There are also small molecule medications that provide temporary relief.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Before Onpattro was released, the treatment options for hATTR were limited.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] After the approval of Onpattro, FDA awarded Alnylam with the Breakthrough Therapy Designation, which is given to drugs that are intended to treat a serious condition and are a substantial improvement over any available therapy.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] It was also awarded Orphan Drug Designations given to those treatments that are intended to safely treat conditions affecting less than 200,000 people.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Along with Onpattro, another RNA interference therapeutic drug has also been discovered (Partisiran) which has property of inhibiting hepatic synthesis of transthyretin.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Target messenger RNA (mRNA) is cleaved as a result by tiny interfering RNAs coupled to the RNA-induced silencing complex.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Patisiran, an investigational RNAi therapeutic drug, uses this process to decrease the production of mutant and wild-type transthyretin by cleaving on 3-untranslated region of transthyretin mRNA.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] In 2019, FDA approved the second RNAi therapy, Givlaari (givosiran) used to treat acute hepatic porphyria (AHP).
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The disease is caused due to the accumulation of toxic porphobilinogen (PBG) molecules which are formed during the production of heme.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] These molecules accumulate in different organs and this can lead to the symptoms or attacks of AHP.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Givlaari is an siRNA drug that downregulates the expression of aminolevulinic acid synthase 1 (ALAS1), a liver enzyme involved in an early step in heme production.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] The downregulation of ALAS1 lowers the levels of neurotoxic intermediates that cause AHP symptoms.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Years of research has led to a greater understanding of siRNA therapies beyond those affecting the liver.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] As of 2019, Alnylam Pharmaceuticals was involved in therapies that may treat amyloidosis and CNS disorders like Huntington's disease and Alzheimer's disease.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] They have also partnered with Regeneron Pharmaceuticals to develop therapies for CNS, eye and liver diseases.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] As of 2020, ONPATTRO and GIVLAARI, were available for commercial application, and two siRNAs, lumasiran (ALN-GO1) and inclisiran, have been submitted for new drug application to the FDA.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Several siRNAs are undergoing phase 3 clinical studies, and more candidates are in the early developmental stage.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] In 2020, Alnylam and Vir pharmaceuticals announced a partnership and have started working on a RNAi therapy that would treat severe cases of COVID-19.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Other companies that have had success in developing a pipeline of siRNA therapies are Dicerna Pharmaceuticals, partnered Eli Lilly and Company and Arrowhead Pharmaceuticals partnered with Johnson and Johnson.
[src:rna-interference/small-interfering-rna] Several other big pharmaceutical companies such as Amgen and AstraZeneca have also invested heavily in siRNA therapies as they see the potential success of this area of biological drugs.
